properties.name: Lake Elingamite Camp Area
properties.description: Toilet, SC and non-SC, picnic tables, playground and lake views. Fires not allowed.

properties.name: Henty Park RV Camping Area
properties.description: Only for RV and Caravans. Free water and dump station. Toilet next to dump station

properties.name: Carters Beach
properties.description: Great campsite on Murray River, very popular among the locals. There are some benches and dry toilets, lots of space to camp. Quite remote and therefore peaceful.

properties.name: The Grotto Sinkhole
properties.description: The Grotto in Morton National Park, tucked away on West Rim walking track, is well worth a visit. After a short, steep climb, you'll be rewarded with views of a crystal shower that cascades over a rocky outcrop.

properties.name: Lorne Foreshore Caravan Park
properties.description: The Lorne Foreshore Caravan Park is located along the scenic Great Ocean Road

properties.name: Slaty Creek Campground - Creswick Regional Park
properties.description: This nice bush camping area with good facilities is located by the creek, among trees. The area is quiet and shaded and it offers scenic views, walking tracks and gold fossicking.

properties.name: Perry Bridge Recreation Area on the Avon River
properties.description: This beautiful camping area with no amenities, except for rubbish bins, is located on the bank of the river and offers plenty of fishing spots and walking tracks. There is also a boat ramp.

properties.name: Italian Flat Campground
properties.description: This spacious and grassy camping area with good facilities is located on the bank of the river. It offers scenic views, walking tracks and plenty of shade, as well as swimming and fishing.

properties.name: Golden Beach RV Rest Stop Area
properties.description: Golden Beach RV Rest Stop Area is suitable for self contained vehicles only. There are toilets available. Pets are allowed.

properties.name: Wulgulmerang Recreation Reserve
properties.description: Wulgulmerang Recreation Reserve camping area offers powered sites for tents,and caravans. Facilities include toilets, showers, water, BBQ, fire place and picnic tables. Pets are allowed.
properties.fees: Camping fees $10 per person per night, plus $5 per night per outlet if power is required

properties.name: Sea Lake Recreation Reserve Caravan Park
properties.description: Sea Lake Recreation Reserve Caravan Park offers powered and unpowered sites suitable for tents, caravans and large rigs. Facilities include toilets, showers, dirnking water, laundromat, BBQ, picnic tables, dump point and mobile phone coverage. Pets are allowed.

properties.name: Glenlyon Mineral Springs Reserve Camping
properties.description: Public toilets, playground are 100m walk from campground. Campground has gas BBQ and covered picnic table. Tap water.

properties.name: Fishermans Point Camping
properties.description: 1km from motorway, SC and non-SC welcome. Toilet, picnic tables and fireplaces.

properties.name: McLoughlins Beach Parking Area
properties.description: Rest area right at the waterfront. There are about 10 spaces to park next to each other. Beautiful views. Picnic tables (some are sheltered) and rubbish bins available. Toilets are clean, but without roof. There are new toilets at the boat ramp - take the footpath for 300m N.

properties.name: Minneha'ha Falls Campground
properties.description: This free campground is located right at the Minneha'ha Falls, 3km of partly gravel road. Public toilets available (off season only one toilet open/accessible by wheelchair). No water. Picnic table available, BYO wood for bonfire. No rubbish bins, take your litter home. No reception.

properties.name: Lake Benalla Camp and Rest Area
properties.description: Basic car parking area next to the skate park, by Lake Benalla. Toilet is located underneath the library building, BBQ nearby. Beautiful walk around the lake.

properties.name: Smoko Camping Area
properties.description: Large bush camping area next to Ovens River. Toilet and picnic tables available, some shade from trees. Nice spot if you want to do a bit of fishing or go for a swim. 700m E of Great Alpine Rd, 90km S of Wangaratta.

properties.name: Skinners Flat Reservoir Camp Area
properties.description: Free campsite located on the edge of the reservoir, available to both self contained and non-self contained. 1km of gravel road to get here.

properties.name: Firth Park Campground Wombat State Forest
properties.description: 6km gravel road to SC and non-SC area. Covered picnic table, fireplaces, toilets, non-drinkable tap water.

properties.name: Major Creek Reserve
properties.description: Free dirt camping area on the banks of Major Creek, NW of the bridge. Drop toilets and picnic tables available. Can be a popular spot during holidays. 14km SW of Nagambie via Odwyer Rd and Mitchellstown Rd.

properties.name: Marlay Point
properties.description: This free campsite at Lake Wellington offers public toilets, BBQ, benches (also sheltered), tap water and rubbish bins. It is a fairly big grassy area right at te waterfront, you will find spot under the trees. The area is not protected and might be windy.

properties.name: Seninis Campground
properties.description: Grassy free camping in Moondarra State Park. Pit toilets and picnic tables available, as well as plenty of shade. Turnoff for campsite is on the W side of Moe-Wahalla Rd, just SE of Moondarra. Take Seninis Track 2km to campsite. Dirt road.

properties.name: North Gardens Campground
properties.description: Large free camping area located in Walhalla. Toilets, picnic tables, bins, BBQs and water available. Lots of space but can be a popular spot and fill up quickly at peak times.

properties.name: Lorne Beach
properties.description: One of the worlds nicest urban beaches, this is a must do when passing through - you can even see parrots here!

properties.name: Warburton Holiday Park
properties.description:
Warburton Holiday Park is working to become a premier camping, caravan and holiday destination in the Yarra Valley.
Only a 75km scenic drive from the heart of Melbourne, it offers a variety of accommodation options, with acres of camp grounds, caravan sites and self-contained cabins, BBQ facilities, as well as a new children’s playground and water-play park. All within a unique setting beside the flowing waters of the Yarra River, nestled in amongst spectacular Australian bush surrounds.
On early morning walks, you might spy the elusive native platypus or enjoy floating along the 1 kilometer river frontage on a lilo, or fishing for a trout while your children play ball sports in the sunshine. There are a range of local walking trails, bike trails and activities for the whole family. Situated only 1.5 kms from the heart of the Warburton township, this historic town is a gateway to all that the Yarra Valley region has to offer. Come and visit us today to see for yourselves.

properties.name: Benalla Tourist Park
properties.description: Benalla Tourist Park offers accommodation for tourists, travellers and families alike.

properties.name: Yarram Holiday Park
properties.description: Yarram Holiday Park is located a stone’s throw from some of the region’s most picturesque landscapes. Take in the exceptional natural beauty at Tarra Bulga National Park, unspoilt beaches at the Ninety Mile Beach, one of Gippsland’s oldest ports at Port Albert, Port Welshpool’s recently reopened Long Jetty and the stunning Agnes Falls. We have Cabins, Ensuite Sites, Powered/Unpowered Sites, Children’s Playground, Jumping Pillow, Pedal Go Carts, Sheltered BBQ and Campfire. The park is pet-friendly with some cabins dedicated to our furry friends.

properties.name: United Backpackers
properties.description:
Opposite the Flinders Street train station, this urban backpackers hostel is also a 3-minute walk from the Yarra River and a 6-minute walk from Federation Square. 

The functional private or dorm-style rooms (with female-only options) feature shared or private bathrooms. All also provide lockers and bedding but do not have air-conditioning.

Wi-Fi is free in communal areas. There's a guest kitchen and a dining room, as well as a basement bar. Other amenities include a 24-hour lounge and laundry facilities, plus a TV room.

properties.name: Wattle Park
properties.description:
Wattle Park features historic buildings, huge gum trees, wattles, seasonal wildflowers and ponds. With an all-abilities playscape, picnic grounds multi-purpose tracks, including the recently upgraded 3.25km walking and running track, this park has something for the whole family. 
There are some 50 bird species in the park. Look for birds including the White-faced Heron and Rainbow Lorikeet, or keep your eyes peeled for a Tawny Frogmouth sitting in a tree. Visit the filtration ponds alongside Damper Creek and see ducks and frogs amongst the native rushes. There is also 20 species of butterflies and 60 species of beetles in the park.

properties.name: Walhalla Goldfields Railway
properties.description: The Walhalla Goldfields Railway is a 762 mm narrow gauge tourist railway located in the Thomson River and Stringers Creek valleys in Gippsland, Victoria, near the former gold-mining town and tourist destination of Walhalla.

properties.name: Mt Buller Alpine Resort
properties.description:
Located just a breezy three-hour drive away from Melbourne, Mt. Buller stands as Australia's most conveniently accessible alpine resort. It beckons visitors seeking the ideal summer retreat, catering to diverse tastes and interests. Whether you plan a brief day trip or an extended getaway, Mt. Buller offers an array of experiences to cherish. From tranquil picnics atop the summit to leisurely strolls and the exhilaration of activities like motorbiking, four-wheel driving, and mountain biking, this destination has it all. 

With its awe-inspiring vistas, pure alpine air, and refreshing summer climate, Mt. Buller presents an idyllic backdrop for relaxation and rejuvenation. Within the charming Mt. Buller Village, you'll discover an assortment of dining establishments and lodging choices, allowing you to savor local cuisine and savor the warm embrace of mountain hospitality. 

Furthermore, Mt. Buller's calendar boasts a captivating lineup of summer events, including food and wine festivals, thrilling mountain biking and cycling competitions, exciting car races, vibrant Easter celebrations, and a wealth of other engaging activities.

properties.name: Mount Samaria State Park
properties.description: Set in tall, shady eucalypt forest, Mount Samaria State Park offers a cool and quiet retreat for beautiful walks, camping and picnicking. The Mount Samaria range incorporates a variety of scenery with spectacular vistas over the Victorian Alps, granite outcrops, high waterfalls and historic remains.

properties.name: Mitchell River Walking Track
properties.description:
The walk starts at Angusvale and follows the Mitchell River as it winds its way down the gorge, ending at the Den of Nargun picnic area. 

Overnight camping is available at Billy Goat Bend which is located about half way along the walk. The walk offers spectacular views from the river to gorge top as well as plenty of birdwatching opportunities.

The track is 18km long - allow 2 days one way.

properties.name: Marysville Kin Playspace
properties.description: The Kin Playspace is an adventure playground located on the former kindergarten site in Marsyville. This playspace caters for children from one to 12 years old and features a broad range of play equipment including an elevated sandpit, slides, roundabout, rope climbing net, dual flying foxes, timber swings and a water play structure. The $1 million re-development features a state-of-the-art children's playground, gardens and statue. This project was made possible by the kind donations made through the Victorian Bushfire Appeal Fund and has been developed by local community groups.

properties.name: Kalorama Park Picnic Ground
properties.description: Kalorama Park is a 1.7-hectare park in the Kalorama suburb of Melbourne, Victoria. It is located on the eastern slopes of Mount Macedon and offers stunning views of the city and surrounding countryside. The park is home to a variety of native Australian plants and animals, including kangaroos, koalas, and possums. There are also a number of walking trails that wind through the park, offering visitors the opportunity to explore the natural beauty of the area.

properties.name: Gooram Falls & Swimming Hole
properties.description:
The Gooram Falls is a beautiful place to visit for a swim and picnic during summer or to rug up in winter and enjoy the views of the rock pools and the water cascading over the rocks. 

The Gooram Falls are west of the Strathbogie Tableland on the Euroa-Mansfield Road. Two-wheel drive access to the carpark is fine.

properties.name: Gippsland Vehicle Collection Motor Museum
properties.description: The Gippsland Vehicle Collection provides south east Australia with an outstanding rotating display of interesting vehicles including cars, motor-bikes, machinery, historic vehicles and auto memorabilia.

properties.name: Flagstaff Hill Maritime Village & Shipwrecked Sound and Laser Show
properties.description: By day or by night Flagstaff Hill Maritime Village & Shipwrecked Sound and Laser Show is a must do - and winner of Victorian Tourism Award Hall of Fame, plus several Museums Australia Awards.

properties.name: East Gippsland Rail Trail
properties.description:
Embark on a picturesque journey from Bairnsdale to Newmerella, winding through playful hills and the serene Colquhoun Forest, where ancient trestle bridges stand as silent witnesses to the past. 

This trail meanders through idyllic countryside, enchanting forests untouched by time, expansive floodplains, the mesmerizing Gippsland Lakes, and ultimately leads you to the awe-inspiring Snowy River. 

Whether you're planning an immersive multi-day adventure or a delightful day trip, this versatile path unveils a diverse tapestry of landscapes. 

Along the way, you'll encounter welcoming villages that offer delectable cuisine and cozy accommodations, making your experience truly unforgettable.

properties.name: Corryong Op Shop
properties.description:
The Corryong Op Shop is a fully stocked, air conditioned second-hand retail shop situated in the heart of the main street of Corryong. They donate all proceeds to the local schools.

The Shop provides an extensive range of second-hand goods including mens, ladies and children's clothing from vintage to modern day, footwear, jewellery, books, DVDs and videos.

properties.name: Cape Otway Lightstation
properties.description: Cape Otway Lightstation is Australia's most important lighthouse. The Light established in 1848 is perched on towering sea cliffs 90 metres above where Bass Straight and Southern Ocean collide. Experience the thrill of stepping out onto the Lighthouse Balcony for awesome views.

properties.name: Tim's Place
properties.description: Tim's Place offers Backpacker and Apartment style accommodation in the village of Halls Gap in the Grampians National Park. It is close to all the walking trails in the Wonderland region of the Grampians. All the walking trails can be explored from the hostel.

properties.name: Dylene Holiday Park Portarlington
properties.description: The park features fully self-contained cabins or park your own caravan and enjoy the charm of the Bellarine Peninsula.

properties.name: Logans Beach Whale Watching Platform
properties.description: The Logans Beach Whale Watching Platform is a wooden deck that offers views of the Southern Right Whale nursery. The Southern Right Whales migrate to Logans Beach every year between June and September to give birth. The whales often swim within a hundred meters of the shore, making them easy to spot from the platform.

properties.name: Shipwreck Creek Campground
properties.description:
Shipwreck Creek Campground offers a secluded camping experience among tall eucalypt trees. 

A great escape from nearby Mallacoota, this small cosy campground is a short walk away from the secluded Shipwreck Beach named after the wreck of The Schah (1837), one of Victoria's oldest shipwrecks.

properties.name: Pakenham Caravan Park
properties.description: Pakenham Caravan Park is an independent family owned park. Located just off the M1Freeway, where the country meets the city. Ideal accommodation base for the corporate traveller, holiday maker or stop over for visiting family and friends.

properties.name: Yinnar RV Stop
properties.description: Overnight accommodation for 8 vehicles/tents on large grass pitches with self-catering (toilet, 20 liters of water). Provision of rubbish bins. Upon arrival, a short message to the operator of the facility is required. Turn off directly from the main road in Hazelwood, but no-very little noise disturbance from the road. Recommendation for places to eat nearby (5 minutes walk): Yinnar Community Hotel (especially on Tuesdays: Hot&Parma Tuesday).

properties.name: Razorback Hut
properties.description: Free Camping next to a hut. Sometimes used by horse groups. Nice spot in tall forest.

properties.name: Woodfield Shearer's Quarters
properties.description: This is a paid campground with toilets, showers. Sleeps 15 in cabins with great kitchen facilities. Plenty of room for large caravans and camper trailers. Call Chris t book ahead.

properties.name: Port Albert Recreation and Racecourse Reserve
properties.description: This area is no longer used for race meets or sporting event, but is a fabulous place to camp. You will need to be self-contained. A donation is suggested.

properties.name: Taylor's Lake Camping Site
properties.description: On the side of a lake, has flush toilets, plenty of shade and grassy areas to stay. Very spacious and with a delightful view on the lake and Grampians on the back ground.

properties.name: Tchum Lake
properties.description: Picturesque lake on the Birchip-Wycheproof Road, 8km East of Birchip. Perfect spot to spend the day, weekend or even park up for the week. Plenty to do and see in the area. Great lake for water skiing, fishing and camping. Couldn’t ask for better facilities with access to toilet, shower and laundry facilities, camp kitchen, BBQ areas, picnic tables, boat ramp, playground and shade shelters.

properties.name: Huggetts Crossing 4wd Camp Area
properties.description: This camping area is at the western edge of the reserve, and is connected to Dermody Camp by the enchanting Avon River Trail. South of here you can get superb forest views from the Green Hill and Huggett lookouts, or head further south to Bulldog Junction to do the walk up to the picturesque summit of Mt Hendrick. Huggetts can only be accessed with a 4WD from Green Hill via the Huggett–Mt Angus Track.

properties.name: Number One Camp
properties.description: Nice cleared camp sites allowing access for both vehicles and tent campers. Drop toilet but no other facilities. Please take rubbish away with you.

properties.name: Gadds Bend Reserve
properties.description: Gadds bend reserve is a grassed level free camping area, on the Murray river , lots of spots for caravans , no amenities so fully self contained vehicles only , beautiful location

properties.name: Coopers Creek Campground
properties.description: Awesome campgrounds on the Thomson river close to Walhalla. Day picnic area with tables and two camping areas with fire pits and toilets.

properties.name: Kalymna Falls Campground
properties.description: Small and beautiful free camping with a toilet and a rainwater tank, if you want to camp are 5 places available.

properties.name: Spoon Bay Campground
properties.description: Free camp with basic facilities on a sandy road. Not good for winter as you will be bogged (sometimes floods). Nice lake view and good for tents and caravans.

properties.name: Andersons Garden Campsite
properties.description: Free campsite in Mount Disappointment State Forest. Creek runs through it.

properties.name: Byaduk caves
properties.description:
The Byaduk Caves are the most extensive set of lava caves in Australia. The caves form an intricate connection of underground tubes, created when the lava from nearby volcano Mt Napier solidified on the surface and molten lava continued to flow underneath. 
Found in Australia's youngest volcanic province at only around 30,000 years old, the caves are largely unweathered and still maintain in their natural state. The largest of the caves measures 18 metres wide, 10 metres high and extends 20 metres below the surface. 
The caves are easily accessible by 2WD vehicles and there is ample parking.

properties.name: Boroka Lookout
properties.description:
Boroka Lookout is a spectacular vantage point in the Grampians National Park, known for its breathtaking views of Halls Gap, Lake Bellfield, the Wonderland Range, the Mount William Range, the Fyans Valley, and the scenic plains beyond the Grampians to the east. The lookout is easily accessible via a short, well-maintained walking track, making it a popular destination for visitors of all ages and abilities.

As you approach the lookout, you are greeted by towering rock formations and fragrant eucalyptus trees. The walking track leads to two viewing platforms, each offering a unique perspective on the surrounding landscape. From the first platform, you can enjoy panoramic views of Halls Gap and Lake Bellfield, nestled amidst the rugged hills. The second platform reveals stunning vistas of the Wonderland Range and the Mount William Range, their peaks piercing the sky.

The views from Boroka Lookout are particularly stunning at sunrise and sunset, when the sky is ablaze with color. The lookout is also a great place to spot wildlife, such as kangaroos, wallabies, and birds. On a clear day, you may even see gliders soaring through the air.

Boroka Lookout is a must-visit for anyone visiting the Grampians National Park. It is a place to relax and soak in the beauty of the natural world. The lookout is also a great starting point for exploring other parts of the park, such as MacKenzie Falls, Reed Lookout, Silverband Falls, and Venus Baths.

Whether you are a keen hiker, a nature lover, or simply looking for a scenic spot to enjoy a picnic, Boroka Lookout is sure to impress. The lookout's stunning views, accessible location, and peaceful atmosphere make it a truly special place to visit. So, on your next trip to the Grampians, be sure to add Boroka Lookout to your itinerary and experience the magic of this enchanting spot.

properties.name: Reeds Lookout & Balconies
properties.description:
Reeds Lookout and The Balconies offer stunning views of the Victoria Valley in the Grampians National Park. Reeds Lookout is accessible via a short, easy walk from the car park, while The Balconies are a 1km hike away. Both lookouts provide panoramic views of the surrounding landscape, including the Victoria Range, the Serra Range, Lake Wartook, and the Mount Difficult Range.

Reeds Lookout is a popular spot for watching the sunset. The lookout is located on a westward-facing ridge, offering clear views of the setting sun.

properties.name: Salmon rocks
properties.description:
Salmon Rocks is a scenic spot in Cape Conran Coastal Park, Victoria. It is a series of exposed rock platforms that are home to a variety of marine life, including salmon.

The rocks are located at the end of a walking track and offer stunning views of the coastline.

properties.name: Owens Hill campsite.
properties.description: Great views of lake Eildon. Not a great deal of flat ground. All dirt, site has a drop toilet.

properties.name: Woolshed Falls
properties.description: Woolshed Falls is a beautiful waterfall located in the Chiltern-Mount Pilot National Park, about 10 minutes drive north of Beechworth, Victoria. The falls are best visited after a heavy rainfall, as the water flow is much more impressive. However, the falls are also beautiful during the dry season. There are two viewing platforms that offer stunning views of the falls, the upper viewing platform is wheelchair accessible. There are a few walking tracks in the area, including a short walk to the base of the falls. The walks are mostly easy and are suitable for all ages. Woolshed Falls is a great place to relax and enjoy the natural beauty of the Australian bush. It is also a popular spot for picnics.

properties.name: Lake Lonsdale Camping Area
properties.description:
Free camp on the edge of Lake Lonsdale. Large spaces for big vans. Can get windy in the evenings.
A patrol officer will collect fees and issue you with a receipt. 
No camping in the sandbar area.
properties.fees:
$12 per night per camp
(Up to 2 adults, 4 children, 1 vehicle with trailer)

properties.name: Port Campbell Discovery Walk
properties.description: The Port Campbell Discovery walk traverses cliff top and dense low coastal heath. It offers wildlife viewing opportunities and unobstructed viewing east, to Sentinel Rock and the 12 Apostles. Look out for wildlife around dusk and dawn!

properties.name: Sheoak Falls
properties.description:
Sheoak Falls is a beautiful waterfall located in the Great Otway National Park. The walk to the falls is relatively easy, taking about 15 minutes from the car park. The track is well-maintained and suitable for all ages and fitness levels. The path winds its way through lush rainforest, passing over several small creeks and waterfalls before reaching the main falls.
The main falls are about 15 meters high and cascade into a deep pool surrounded by rocks and ferns. The pool is a popular spot for swimming, but it is important to be careful as the rocks can be slippery.
There are several picnic areas located near the falls, as well as a barbecue. There are also toilets and changing facilities available.

properties.name: Castle Cover Lookout Walk
properties.description: Castle Cove Lookout trail, discover this 3.5-km out-and-back trail near Glenaire, Victoria. Generally considered an easy route, it takes an average of 1 h 4 min to complete. This is a very popular area for hiking and walking, so you'll likely encounter other people while exploring. The trail is open year-round and is beautiful to visit anytime.

properties.name: The Crags
properties.description: The Crags in Yambuk, Victoria, Australia, is a stunning coastal formation that combines dramatic cliffs with breathtaking ocean views. This natural wonder is known for its towering limestone stacks and rugged terrain, making it a popular destination for nature enthusiasts and photographers. The area offers walking trails that allow visitors to explore the coastline, observe seabirds and, during the right season, even witness migrating whales.

properties.name: Erskine Falls
properties.description:
Erskine Falls, nestled in Australia's Otway Ranges, is a natural wonder to behold. Cascading from a towering height, the waterfall plunges into a lush rainforest gorge below.

A short hike through pristine wilderness leads to a viewing platform, offering a breathtaking glimpse of this majestic spectacle, making it a photographer's paradise.

properties.name: The Island Camp Ground Lake Eildon
properties.description: Lake Eildon National Park offers a variety of settings to explore; from open bush in the North, to dense vegetation in the South and East. Free  dog friendly camping,(low water line) fishing, boating, kayaking, 4x4, bushwalking, bird watching (wedge tailed eagle) back to basics camping. Toilets within walking distance, plenty of room along Plantation rd to set up camp.

properties.name: Mt. Oberon Summit Track
properties.description:
The Mt. Oberon Summit Track is a picturesque hiking trail located in Wilsons Promontory National Park, Victoria, Australia. 

It offers a moderately challenging ascent to the summit of Mt. Oberon, providing stunning panoramic views of the surrounding landscapes, including Tidal River, pristine beaches, and the rugged coastline. 

This 3.4-kilometre round-trip hike showcases diverse flora and is a popular destination for nature enthusiasts and photographers seeking breathtaking vistas of the Australian wilderness.

properties.name: Tower Hill Wildlife Reserve
properties.description: The Tower Hill Wildlife Reserve, nestled in the heart of Victoria, is a remarkable conservation area that showcases the region's natural beauty and rich biodiversity. Formed by a volcanic crater, this unique reserve offers a diverse range of ecosystems, including wetlands, woodlands, and grasslands. Visitors can explore a network of walking trails that wind through these habitats, providing opportunities to observe native wildlife such as kangaroos, emus, koalas, and a variety of bird species. With informative visitor centers and picnic areas, Tower Hill is an educational and scenic destination that allows you to connect with Australia's captivating natural heritage.

properties.name: Aire River Campgrounds
properties.description: The Aire River campground has a range of campsites located on the west side of Aire River and within a short walking distance from the river. Most sites are on open, level, grassed areas with no or limited shade. Some sites have a designated fireplace with a hotplate and picnic tables. There is no mains power in this toilet or on the campground. Water for camp use can be accessed from a tap connected to the rainwater tank at the car park next to the toilets.

properties.name: Triplet Falls
properties.description:
Triplet Falls is a waterfall located in the Great Otway National Park in Victoria, Australia. It is a popular tourist destination, known for its beauty and its easy accessibility. 

The waterfall is formed by three streams that cascade down a rock face into a pool below. The water is clear and clean, and the pool is a popular spot for swimming and picnicking. 

Triplet Falls is located just a short walk from the car park, making it an easy destination for people of all ages and abilities. There is also a picnic area and toilets located near the waterfall.

properties.name: Lake Willam Hovel
properties.description: Awesome fishing spot with no vehicle access - walk in only

properties.name: Kirbys campground
properties.description: Pretty flat campground with a few trees about. Easy access for 2wd and campervans. No water. Drop loo.

properties.name: Allenvale Mill Site
properties.description:
Relax at camp or explore one of the many walking trails in the area. Platypus are known to inhabit St George River, so be sure to keep an eye out at dawn and dusk.

Allenvale Campground contains 20 walk-in campsites, each accommodating up to six people. All campsites are unpowered and are suitable for tents only. There is no direct vehicle access to the campsites. A carpark is located close by (approximately 230 meters). Campground facilities include non-flush toilets and low tables/seats. There are no fireplaces provided, and fires are not allowed. Please bring your own fuel stove or gas barbeque for cooking. Advanced bookings and payment are required year-round.

properties.name: Wilderness Coast Walk
properties.description:
The Wilderness Coast Walk extends along the wild coast of far-east Gippsland. Trek isolated stretches of coastline, including the Sandpatch Wilderness Area, past the historic Point Hicks Lighthouse, secluded coves and through pristine landscapes teeming with native wildlife. 

Location: Croajingolong National Park 
Distance: 45 kilometres one way 
Duration: Three to four days 
Grade: Level Four - Bushwalking experience and a good level of fitness required. 

Tracks may be long, rough and very steep. Directional signage may be limited. Walks may be more than 20 kilometres.

properties.name: Upper Yarra Reservoir Park
properties.description: Upper Yarra Reservoir Park is a popular destination for day-trippers and campers, offering natural wonders, historical sites and built facilities to enjoy getting into nature. There are a number of walking trails that wind through the park, offering stunning views of the surrounding countryside.

properties.name: Timandra by the Sea
properties.description: Guests are often taken aback by the beautiful garden that is Timandra by the Sea. This sustainable, award winning garden is loved by adults and children alike. It is a natural garden and a haven for many different birds and koalas.

properties.name: The Heritage Walk - Violet Town
properties.description: Take a stroll around Violet Town and discover some of the parts that make up the history of this small town. The Heritage Walk is made up of 18 points of interest, with visitors able to commence the walk at any one of the locations.

properties.name: Nioka Bush Camp
properties.description:
Nioka Bush Camp is a quiet retreat away from the stresses of city life. Stay overnight in the great outdoors, camping or in bunkhouse accommodation. 

Explore the sights and sounds of of the bush on a pleasant bushwalk. The wildlife is varied and you might catch a glimpse of an Eastern Grey Kangaroo or a Sugar Gliders.

properties.name: Luna Park Melbourne
properties.description:
Luna Park Melbourne is an iconic amusement park located on the picturesque St Kilda foreshore in Australia. Opened in 1912, it's a must-visit destination for travelers seeking fun and nostalgia. 

The park features a distinctive entrance with a giant grinning face, and once inside, you'll discover a range of thrilling rides, including roller coasters, carousels, and a historic Scenic Railway. Luna Park's vibrant atmosphere, with its neon lights and carnival games, offers an enchanting experience for visitors of all ages. 

Enjoy the scenic views of Port Phillip Bay, indulge in delicious snacks, and create lasting memories in this lively and historic amusement park.

properties.name: Lake Elizabeth
properties.description: Lake Elizabeth is hidden deep in the Otways and discover its inspiring beauty with heavily timbered flanks and calm waters punctuated by the trunks of dead trees, drowned when the valley was flooded more than 50 years ago to form this perched lake. The elusive platypus can be found in the waters of the lake - wake up early or head to Lake Elizabeth at dusk to catch a glimpse of these shy Australian natives. The campground sits on the bank of the east branch of the Barwon River sheltered by tall Eucalypts trees. A scenic 20 minute walk takes you to Lake Elizabeth.

properties.name: Falls Creek All Season Alpine Resort
properties.description:
Winter at Falls Creek All Season Alpine Resort offers world-class skiing and snowboarding on over 92 downhill runs, as well as snowshoeing, cross-country skiing, and snowmobile tours. The resort transforms into a snowy wonderland, perfect for winter sports enthusiasts. 

In the summer, Falls Creek transforms into a lush alpine paradise with hiking and mountain biking trails galore. Explore the alpine wildflowers, go fishing in mountain streams, or take a scenic chairlift ride for breathtaking views. You can also enjoy horseback riding, tennis, and golf. The warm weather offers endless outdoor adventures in this picturesque Australian alpine setting.

properties.name: Fairy Park
properties.description: Family attraction Fairy Park, located just 60 minutes from Melbourne and 30 minutes from Geelong, has taken over 50 years to create. Dedicated to tales, myths and legends the park features 32 scenes housed in awe-inspiring castles, cottages and caves set among beautifully manicured gardens.

properties.name: Dookie Rail Trail
properties.description: The Dookie Rail Trail traverses open fertile farmland with rolling hills in the distance. Set at the base of Mt Saddleback, after a gentle climb you are rewarded with stunning views of Mt Major and Gentle Annie Hill.

properties.name: Cardinia Reservoir Park
properties.description:
Cardinia Reservoir itself is a stunning expanse of water. Don't miss the views from the lookouts, which offer spectacular vistas over the water and the surrounding district.

Take one of the several walks through the park for an opportunity to spot some of the wildlife that call Cardinia Reservoir home. Try the Tea-tree Trail, which goes through bushland from Duffy's Lookout to the Observation carpark - signs along this trail introduce you to a variety of plants and animals.

properties.name: Buxton Mountain Bike Path
properties.description: Buxton Mountain Bike Park is situated within the Black Range State forest, approximately 100 km north east of Melbourne. There is around 23 km of purpose built mountain bike single track in the park that can be ridden in a number of different length loops. The trails are ridden in one direction and are signed accordingly. The trails are characterised by gentle climbs and fast flowing descents. When ridden with care, the majority of trails are suitable for riders of all abilities.

properties.name: Australian Centre for the Moving Image
properties.description:
Located in the heart of Melbourne's Fed Square, ACMI (formerly Australian Centre for the Moving Image) celebrates the wonder and power of the world's most democratic artform - fostering the next generation of makers, players and watchers. 

ACMI's vibrant calendar of exhibitions, screenings, commissions, festivals, and industry and education programs explore the stories, technologies and artists that create our shared screen culture.

properties.name: Yackandandah Lake Picnic Reserve
properties.description: Yackandandah Lake Picnic Reserve is a 40-hectare reserve that offers a variety of activities, including fishing, swimming, boating, and walking. It is a popular spot for families and is a great place to relax and enjoy the natural surroundings.

properties.name: Water Wheel Beach Tavern
properties.description:
Caravan, vans tents cars. Literally on the 90 mile beach. Great fishing boating, 4wd, birdwatching and the only pub located right on the ocean. You would be nuts to drive by the LAKE TYERS BEACH,  turn off. Located only seven minutes drive east of LAKES ENTRANCE. 
03 51565855 if you need info 
waterwheelbeachtavern@hotmail. Com

properties.name: Eastern beach Geelong
properties.description: Geelong’s waterfront is one of the most gorgeous in all of Australia. Check out Eastern Beach, a funky art-deco inspired hotspot loved by the locals.

properties.name: Kergunyah Bridge Reserve Campground
properties.description: Nice campground located close to the shops and also in the close neighbourhood of Kergunyah Caravan Park

properties.name: Richardsons bend
properties.description: Free camping ground with no amenities. Dry weather access only! Great for relaxing, swimming and fishing. Bring drinking water with you.

properties.name: Farran's Lookout
properties.description:
Farran's Lookout is a scenic lookout located on the Murray River Road, between Tintaldra and Towong in Victoria, Australia. It offers stunning views of the Upper Murray River, the Australian Alps in the distance, and the lush green countryside below.

In addition to its scenic views, Farran's Lookout is also a great place to spot wildlife. Visitors can often see kangaroos, wallabies, and other native animals grazing in the nearby fields. The lookout is also a popular spot for birdwatching.

properties.name: St Kilda Pier
properties.description:
St. Kilda Pier is an iconic destination located in Melbourne, Australia. This picturesque pier stretches out into Port Phillip Bay, offering breathtaking views of the city skyline and the bay. 

Visitors can stroll along the boardwalk, spotting local wildlife like penguins and various seabirds, especially at dusk when the penguins return from their daily fishing trips. 

At the end of the pier, you'll find the historic St. Kilda Pavilion, housing a stylish cafe where you can enjoy coffee or refreshments.

properties.name: Raymond Island Koala Trail
properties.description: The Raymond Island Koala Trail is a 1.2-kilometre loop walk located on Raymond Island in Victoria, Australia. The trail also passes through rainforest, wetlands, and beaches.

properties.name: Brown Brothers Winery
properties.description: For self contained vehicles only in the Browns Brothers staff car park. Especially handy after a few tastings.

properties.name: Noojee Trestle Bridge Rail Trail
properties.description:
The Noojee Trestle Bridge Rail Trail is a short, 3-kilometre long rail trail in Noojee, Victoria, Australia. It is primarily features an impressive 100-metre long trestle bridge. The trail follows the alignment of the former Noojee railway line, which was built in 1919 to transport timber from the surrounding hills. The railway closed in 1973, but the trestle bridge was saved from demolition and restored in 2006.

The Noojee Trestle Bridge Rail Trail is a popular spot for walking, cycling, and horse riding. It is also a good place to see wildlife, such as kangaroos, possums, and birds. The trail is well-maintained and easy to follow, making it a great option for all ages and abilities.

properties.name: Karelia Alpine Lodge
properties.description:
Karelia Alpine Lodge is a unique Austrian Swiss Chalet in Falls Creek. 

Karelia on Falls is the only four star rated lodge and offers the finest Austrian-Swiss chalet accommodation set in the old and traditional romantic Tyrolean Alpine Style. The ski lodge is close to Falls Express chair lift and that is the clo...

properties.name: Broken Creek Bush Camp
properties.description:
Located just off the Midland Highway, ten minutes from Benalla and 30 minutes from Shepparton, Broken Creek Bush Camp gives you the chance to enjoy the rural countryside, while still being close to amenities, towns and tourist attractions. 

Offering a camping experience that is safer than 'free camping'.

properties.name: Waterfalls Campground
properties.description: This lovely bush camping area with good facilities is located by the Number Two Creek and offers scenic surrounding, good shade, plenty of walking tracks and hiking trails. Suitable for caravans and camper trailers.

properties.name: Walshs Bend Camp
properties.description: This nice campground with no amenities is located on the banks of the river in the woods, and it offers both sunny and shaded sites. There are a few walking tracks, fishing spots and water sports opportunities available - kayaking and swimming are both popular here. Watch for overhead branches and falling limbs! 4WD recommended and not suitable for big rigs.

properties.name: Trawool Reservoir - Tallarook State Forest
properties.description: This waterside area is a popular fishing destination among travellers and the locals alike. It has no amenities and camping in vehicles is only possible from the parking area. If you have a tent, walk 100m towards the river, where the campsite is. There are no facilities provided and access is recommended by 4WD.

properties.name: Torrumbarry Weir - Murray River Reserve
properties.description: This large and dispersed camping area is located along the bank of Murray River, around 1 km away from the Weir. There are plenty of level and relatively shaded sites to camp on, however the only facilities here are the toilets which are located by the weir. It is located only 20 mins away from town and offers good swimming and fishing. To access, take the dirt road marked by the GPS coordinates. Best suited for self-contained vehicles.

properties.name: Stockmans Reward - Upper Big River State Forest
properties.description: This riverside campground is located well off the road, but can be easily accessed by a conventional vehicle. It is dispersed and large, the camping areas are designated, and it is suitable for bigger groups. The Big River - dubbed by heritage authorities 'the scenic heart of the forested valley' - provides great fishing. There are pleasant walking and 4WD trails available around.

properties.name: Shady's Place Camp Area - Briagolong State Forest
properties.description: Creek side camping area with no facilities, other than picnic tables. It is spacious and level and has plenty of shade. It is accessible by 4WD only and offers pleasant and scenic walks.

properties.name: Scotts Beach - Cobram Regional Park
properties.description: Lovely stretch of bush campground by the Murray River located close to town, some 500m off the main road. This site provides good amenities and fishing. There is a good river access with pleasant grassy beach.

properties.name: Reeves Beach Coastal Reserve
properties.description: This campground is located a stone's throw from the beach, just behind the dunes. It has toilet facilities and it's easily accessible off the main road. There are trees scattered here and there for shade and the site is sheltered from the sea breeze.

properties.name: Parolas Bend - Lower Ovens Regional Park
properties.description: This nice bush camping area with no amenities, except for rubbish bins, is located on the banks of the river, approx. 2.5km from the highway. It offers scenic views, plenty of shade and a fishing spot. Gets boggy in wet weather.

properties.name: Paradise Beach Campground
properties.description: This beautiful camping area with good amenities is located beside the beach, off the main road. It offers approx. 50 individual sites, scenic Ocean views, walking tracks and good fishing and swimming. The beach is long and sandy, and there is some shade, too. You need reservations to stay at this campground.

properties.name: Ovens Billabong
properties.description: This peaceful bush camping with no amenities is located off Oxley Flats Rd, beside the river. It offers many water activities, such as swimming, kayaking and fishing. There is some shade available.

properties.name: Nyah Recreation Reserve
properties.description: This dispersed, large and grassy riverside camp is located on the bank of the Murray River, just in town. It has very good amenities, but there are no toilets near the camping area. Incl. A dump point and a boat ramp. It offers plenty of shade, good swimming and fishing, as well as all the benefits of a town location. Maximum stay is 7 days and it is available to SC vehicles only.

properties.name: Noonans Flat Camping Area
properties.description: This is a well signposted bush campground with good facilities, located by the Howqua River well into the wilderness. It offers scenic treks, 4WD trails as well as good fishing. There is a hut, however please note that it's not available to visitors (unless you have made arrangements with the owners). This site can be seasonally closed, so check before going. 4WD access only.

properties.name: Murrayville East Rest Area
properties.description: Nice, gravel, drive-through rest area with basic facilities, located just off the highway. You can follow a dirt track to find a shaded spot away from the traffic. Suitable for big rigs.

properties.name: Mokoan Rest Area
properties.description: There are two rest areas with good facilities accessible for north- and southbound traffic. They are both large and situated a fair distance away from the highway to keep it quiet. There are designated parking spaces, but no shade.

properties.name: Longwarry North Rest Area
properties.description: Spacious rest area with good facilities. It has a drive-through layout and a designated parking section for big vehicles (incl. trucks, caravans and motorhomes). The toilets are well-kept, the surface is gravel and grassy, and accessing this site is easy. There is some shade available, and the traffic noise is low due to the distance between the highway and parking area. 20hrs limit applies, for westbound traffic only.

properties.name: Lake Bael Bael
properties.description: This pleasant bush camping area with no amenities is located by the north-west and south-west edges of the Lake Bael Bael. The area is quiet and peaceful with swimming, canoeing and fishing permitted here.

properties.name: Kyneton Mineral Springs Reserve
properties.description: This beautiful and shaded rest area with good amenities (incl. toilets and fresh mineral spring water) is located on the bank of the Campaspe River, approx. 2.5km from Kyneton. There is a service station just on the opposite side and a maximum stay of 48hrs applies.

properties.name: King Parrot Creek Rest Area
properties.description: This large and gravel rest area is situated by a creek, among many trees. There are no facilities other than a picnic table. The surface is level, however, the access road into the rest area is a bit difficult to manoeuvre. King Parrot creek is good for fishing.

properties.name: Merrington campground
properties.description: This is a large and level area where a cricket ground used to be. There are basic amenities as well as 4WD tracks waiting to be explored. Access to this site is off Walhalla Rd and includes some creek crossing. Suitable for 4WD only.

properties.name: Jim Bullock Camp Area - Big River State Forest
properties.description: This scenic, shaded camping area with toilets is located on the bank of the river, by the Eildon-Jamieson Road, and offers scenic views and good fishing opportunities. There are 4WD tracks nearby. Suitable for camper trailers.

properties.name: Horseshoe Beach - Cobram Regional Park
properties.description: Bush camping area located on the bank of the Murray River. There are plenty of shaded and sunny camping areas and enough privacy, but no amenities. The surface is level and grassy and a nice stretch of beach is available next to the boat ramp. This site is accessible by all vehicles.

properties.name: Hiscocks Crossing - Crawford River Regional Park
properties.description: This camping area consists of spacious and level clearing and some sloping bush campsites - pitching a tent is recommended. There are basic facilities available to visitors and the site is accessible in dry weather, by 4WD only. There are no river views at this campground.

properties.name: Great Divide Service Centre Rest Area
properties.description: This overnight rest area is located off the highway (on both sides), at the service centre. It offers good facilities and a variety of takeaway meals and drinks.

properties.name: Glendinning Campground - Rocklands Reservoir
properties.description: This large and grassy campsite is Rocklands Reservoir's most south-western landmark. It has clean facilities and offers good fishing, swimming, water sports and treks. It is easily accessible by all vehicles and has no max. stay.

properties.name: Frosts Reserve
properties.description: This shaded bush campsite with no amenities is located on the bank of the Ovens Rivers. Swimming, fishing and other activities related to water sports are permitted here.

properties.name: Hynes Camping Reserve
properties.description: Hynes Camping Reserve is a grassy, lakeside camping site with shade provided by yellow gum trees. Toilets and wood BBQ are free of charge; Hot showers are 10c. Bookings are required in peak season, as this is a popular fishing spot.

properties.name: Wallagaraugh River Retreat
properties.description: Cabins and campsites along the Wallagaraugh river, situated in a unique wilderness area.

properties.name: Murrindindi Scenic Reserve
properties.description: Murrindindi Scenic Reserve has a few campsites spread throughout the park. All have access to a pit toilet, and picnic tables and fire pits are available as well. Permits must be acquired before setting up camp.

properties.name: Nariel Creek Recreation Reserve
properties.description: Nariel Creek Recreation Reserve camping area offers sites for vehicle based camping, caravans and camper trailers. Facilities include toilets, picnic tables and fireplace. Activities include fishing and swimming in Nariel Creek. There is a maximum stay of 48 hours. Bookings and enquired can be made through the Corryong Visitor Centre.

properties.name: Tallangatta Showgrounds
properties.description: Tallangatta Showgrounds camping area provides powered and unpowered sites suitable for tents, caravans and long rigs. Facilities include toilets, showers, bins and water. A short walk into town as well as a walking trail around Lake Hume. Call before arrival.

properties.name: Woomelang RV Stop
properties.description: Woomelang RV Stop provides 2 powered sites. There are toilets available. Donation requested.

properties.name: Underbool Recreation Reserve
properties.description: Located on the Murray Hwy, between Sunset and Wyperfeld National Parks, Underbool Recreation Reserve provides sites for vehicles based camping, caravans and camper trailers. Facilities include toilets, showers and playground. Enquires can be made through the Underbool General Store.

properties.name: Lake Meran
properties.description: Lake Meran campground is located on the southern shore of Lake Meran in Leaghur State Park. To reach the camp site you will follow the Chamerlain and Lake Meran tracks then turn North onto Vallance Track. Sites are suitable for vehicle based camping. Facilities include wood fireplace and picnic tables.

properties.name: Jack Emmett Billabong
properties.description: Rupanyup Memorial Park is located adjacent to the Jack Emmet Billabong and provides powered and unpowered sites. Facilities include amenities block, BBQ area, playground, picnic area and bins. Local attractions include Jack's walking track and Wood's Museum.

properties.name: The Quarries Campground
properties.description: The Quarries Campground is located in Briagolong State Forest.  It offers sites for vehicle based camping, caravans and camper trailers. Facilities include toilets, wood fireplaces, (BYO Wood) playground, picnic tables and shelter. There is a local swimming spot. Free camping site however donations towards maintenance at the Reserve can be paid at the General Store. All money raised goes back into improving the camping area.

properties.name: Shallow Inlet Campground
properties.description: Located 4km west of Yanakie, Shallow Inlet Camping area provides campsites suitable for vehicle based camping, caravans and camper trailers. Facilities include toilets. Activities include swimming, fishing, canoeing and walking trails. Fires are not allowed. The campground is open November to Easter only. Long drop toilets(very clean) large and private camp areas.

properties.name: Ensay Recreation Ground
properties.description: Ensay Recreation Ground provides powered sites for vehicle based camping, camper trailers and caravans. Facilities include toilets, showers, BBQ, fireplace and picnic tables and shelter. There is also tennis courts and a large sports oval. Activities include swimming, fishing and walking trails. Camping fees can be paid at the general store.

properties.name: Underbool Rest Area
properties.description: Located adjacent to the Maliee Highway, Underbool Rest Area offers unpowered sites suitable for motorhomes and caravans. Facilities include toilets, water, BBQ and picnic tables. Pets are allowed. There is an honesty box available for power use.

properties.name: Green Lake Recreation Reserve
properties.description: Green Lake Recreation Reserve camping area is suitable for tents, large caravans and motorhomes. Facilities include toilets. Water needs to be treated before drinking. There is mobile phone reception. Dogs are allowed.

properties.name: Kevington Hotel Campground
properties.description: Kevington Hotel Campground offers 10 camp sites. Facilities include toilets and showers for $2. Bookings are made through the Kevington Hotel. The Goulburn River offers swimming holes and fishing spots.

properties.name: Nug Nug Reserve
properties.description: Located in North East Victoria, Nug Nug Reserve is surrounded by Mount Buffalo National Park. The camping area offers powered and unpowered sites for tents, cravans and motorhomes. Facilities include toilets, cold showers, picnic tables, tennis court, basketball/netball court, fireplaces and BBQ. Local attractions include Lake Buffalo for swimming, fishing and waterskiing, and mount Buffalo for horse riding, rock climbing or hiking.  Advanced bookings are not available.
properties.fees: AUD $5 per adult per night $1 per night for child (0-5 yrs free)

properties.name: Lake Charlegrark Campground
properties.description: Lake Charlegrark Campground offers boating, swimming, waterskiing, canoeing,and fishing. The campsite offers powered sites, suitalbe for vehicle based camping, camper trailers and campervans. Facilities include hot showers, drinking water, wood fireplace, picnic tables and shelter area. Bookings are recommended.

properties.name: Centenary Park Campground
properties.description: Centenary campground offers unpowered sites suitable for tents, camping trailers and caravans. Facilities include toilets, water, fireplaces, picnic tables and picnic shelter. You will need to bring your own wood. In there area you can enjoy a variety of walking trails and cycling,.

properties.name: Lascelles Camping Ground
properties.description: Lascelles Camping Ground offers affordable powerd and unpowered sites for tents, and small or large caravans. Facilities include hot showers, toilets, BBQ, picnic tables, childrens play area, and mobile phone coverage. Meals are available to purchase on site.

properties.name: Willaura Recreation Grounds
properties.description: Willaura Recreation Grounds is located in Victoria. This campsite is suitable for tents, caravans, camper trailers. Not suitable for larger vehicles. There are limited powered sites. Showers and water available for a fee.

properties.name: Casuarina Campground Wyperfeld National Park
properties.description: Located in the northern Pine Plains of Wyperfeld National Park, you'll find Casuarina Campground. There is a circular walking track to Bracky Well. Facilities include water, on-site info, toilets, fireplaces and picnic tables. No bookings are taken.

properties.name: Aberfeldy River Camping Area
properties.description: Aberfeldy River camping area is a free campsite located on the Aberfeldy River in the north-easter part of Baw Baw National park. There are 7 sites available, suitable for camper trailers and vehilce-based camping. Facilities include drop toilets and wood fireplaces. Bring firewood and check firebans. Non-potable water available from the river, must be boiled before drinking. Enjoy whitewater rafting on the Thomson River or climb to the top of Mt. St Gwinear for great views of the valley.
properties.fees: AUD $11.70 per adult or $13 per person (Peak season)

properties.name: Buandik Campground
properties.description:
Situated at the base of the Victoria Range beside a creek, pitch your tent or bring your caravan to Buandik Campground.

This is a great place to base yourself and explore the Victoria Range and Victoria Valley areas by four wheel drive. Located in one of the more remote areas of the park, this campground offers tranquility amongst an open eucalypt forest setting.

There are 13 sites suitable for tent-based camping with adjacent vehicle parking, and four drive-in sites suitable for camper trailers, caravans and campervans. Each site at Buandik Campground accommodates a maximum of six people. Sites are unpowered and there are non-flush toilets.

Don't miss the chance to walk up Billimina Creek to Buandik (Jadawadjali) Falls. From there you can continue up the hill to Billimina Shelter. Once a meeting place for the Jadawadjali people, it's covered with over 2,500 motifs made of red ochre bar strokes.

Not far away, another walk takes in the Aboriginal rock art shelter of Manja. For more information on local Aboriginal culture, visit Brambuk the National Park and Cultural Centre in Halls Gap.

properties.name: Fortes Picnic Ground - Mt Cole State Forest
properties.description: Grassy picnic ground with basic amenities. It offers scenic views and many walking tracks. It is shaded and easily accessible for all vehicles.

properties.name: Eustace Creek Camping - Lake Dartmouth Dam
properties.description: This is the only campsite on Lake Dartmouth that can be reached by car, rather than a boat. It has good amenities, is scenically located and provides access to many great hiking trails and water sports (except for water skiing, which is forbidden on the lake), as well as fishing and swimming. 4x4 vehicles are recommended to drive to the site via the Eustace Gap Track which runs off the Corryong - Benambra Road.

properties.name: Doolans Bend - River Murray Reserve
properties.description: Level camping area located on the bank of the Murray River, easily accessible via a dirt track. It boasts plenty of camping spots, including shaded and sunny areas, but no amenities.

properties.name: Ditchfields Campground - Mt Cole State Forest
properties.description: This large, shaded and level campsite is located halfway up Mt Cole. It has new amenities (which incl. toilets) and provides a great gateway to many horse riding trails and walks. While the parking areas might be limited, there is plenty of space to pitch a tent on a grassy clearing. Recommended 4WD access.

properties.name: Dicks Bend Camp Area
properties.description: This level camping area is located on the bank of the Murray River and is easily accessible via a dirt track. There are plenty of shaded and sunny camping spots, but no amenities.

properties.name: Cork Oaks Picnic Area - Mount Beckworth Scenic Reserve
properties.description: Mount Beckworth Scenic Reserve offers spectacular views and a diversity of plants and flowers. This picnic area provides tables, fireplaces and a toilet. Camping is allowed for short stays. The park offers a rich variety of activities like mountain biking and horse riding.

properties.name: Comet Flat - Woods Point
properties.description: This remote and serene location offers basic facilities and great river access with all the swimming and fishing at your doorstep. The campground is situated 4km south east of Woods Point and is accessible by 4WD only.

properties.name: Chaffe Creek Camp Area - Lower Big River
properties.description: Large riverside camp ground providing plenty of camping spots and shade with basic facilities. Suitable for big groups and accessible by conventional vehicles. Please take your rubbish with you.

properties.name: Cameron's Track Campground - Pyrenees State Forest
properties.description: This picturesque campground is located up in the mountains, yet it is easily accessible by all vehicles. Shade is plentiful, but space is quite limited, so caravans and big rigs might prefer to stop at a nearby Waterfall Picnic Area. This site has facilities.

properties.name: Boyds Bridge Camping Area
properties.description: This easily accessible and scenic riverside camp ground is located in a spacious clearing 1.1km off the main road. It doesn't provide any amenities, other than a picnic table and rubbish bins.

properties.name: Big Billy Bore Camping Area
properties.description: Secluded camping area located in a state forest providing basic facilities. Good base camp for exploring Wyperfeld and Big Desert.

properties.name: Bealiba Reservoir
properties.description: Large and grassy camping area with basic facilities. It is maintained by local volunteers, therefore clean and peaceful. Perfect spot for water-related activities. Please leave a donation.

properties.name: Snowy River Picnic Area
properties.description: Next to quiet road, SC only. Has picnic tables.

properties.name: Glenlyon Recreation Reserve Camping
properties.description: Shares facilities with Glenlyon Mineral Springs Reserve - 100m walk between reserves.

properties.name: Lake Hamilton Rest Area
properties.description:
Sealed road in, sealed and grass parking.

Gas BBQ, hot shower, toilets, playground, tap water, fireplace, general rubbish and recycling bins.

NO CAMPING

properties.name: Ess Lagoon Camp Area
properties.description: Large grass area, Self-Contained campervans only. Picnic tables, rubbish bins, fireplaces, fishing and a jetty.

properties.name: Dingo Creek Reserve
properties.description: A beautiful place to camp! After 1.6 gravel road, you end up right in the forests and at the creek. There is a picnic bench but no other facilities. If it's rainy, the place is muddy and most sites will only be accessible by a 4WD. 5 places for normal campervans.

properties.name: Merbein Common Camping
properties.description: Dirt campsite on banks of the Murray River.

properties.name: Horseshoe Bend Camping
properties.description: Nice campsite on the edge of the Murray River. 200 metres of dirt road, slightly rutted, to get to spot. Lots of areas to pull up in. No facilities.

properties.name: Canadian Gully Bushland Reserve
properties.description: Large dirt rest area just off Western Hwy next to the lake. Picnic tables and shade available. 57km SE of Horsham.

properties.name: Swanpool Reserve
properties.description: Free camp area just off Midland Hwy at the S end of Swanpool. Toilets available, but it is for SC only. Located on Swanpool-Lima Rd. Max stay: 24hrs.

properties.name: Lake Crosbie Campground
properties.description: Free camping area in Murray Sunset National Park next to the lake. Non-flush toilets, picnic tables and BBQs available. 14km N of Linga, via Pink Lakes Rd (dirt road). Signposted.

properties.name: OTIT Camping Area
properties.description: Free camp area on the NE side of the lake in Lake Albacutya Regional Park. Non-flush toilets and picnic tables provided. Lake can be dry. 9km NW of Yaapeet via Hopetoun-Yaapeet Rd and Lush Rd. Last 2km is dirt road.

properties.name: Melville Caves Campground
properties.description: Free bush camping area in Kooyoora State Park. Non-flush toilets and picnic tables available, please take your rubbish with you. Limited flat spaces. Located on Melville Caves Rd, 8km N of Rheola via Dunolly-Wedderburn Rd.

properties.name: Bellbird Creek Hotel Rest Area
properties.description: This campground is located just by the Bellbird Creek Hotel, off the highway. Before setting up your camp, please talk to the friendly owners at the Hotel. 24hrs limit.

properties.name: Ada River Campground
properties.description: Large grassy camp area near Errinundra National Park beside Ada River. Toilets, picnic tables and shade available. 29km N of Princes Hwy via Combienbar Rd and Errinundra Valley Rd. Dirt road.

properties.name: Nevins Beach East
properties.description: Basic bush camping next to river in Murray River Reserve. No facilities but you can swim and fish in the river. 20km NW of Yarrawonga via Murray Valley Hwy, Reedys Rd and Nevins Track. Ground can be bumpy.

properties.name: Lake Tyrrell Rest Area
properties.description: Large parking area with views over Lake Tyrell. No facilities and little road noise.  Day use only

properties.name: Beazleys Bridge Rest Area
properties.description: Shady grass rest area just back from Navarre Rd. Picnic tables available but please take your rubbish with you. 14km SW of St Arnaud. Sign out front.

properties.name: Italian Flat Campground
properties.description: Large grassy camp area next to Dargo River. Toilets, picnic tables, BBQs and shade available. Located on Upper Dargo Rd, 9km N of Dargo. Winding dirt road so take care in large vehicles. Signposted.

properties.name: Blue Gum Flat
properties.description: Free camping next to Lake Eildon in Delatite Arm Reserve. Toilets available along with fishing in the lake. On Delatite Plantation Rd, 9km W of Goughs Bay via Walshs Rd.

properties.name: Snakes Reserve
properties.description: Large grassy camping area next to Goulburn River. Toilets available, please take your rubbish with you. Also a nice area for swimming and fishing. 2km N of Knockwood or 18km SE of Kevington on dirt road. Easy to spot as there is a sign at the entrance.

properties.name: Sheepwash Lagoon Rest Area
properties.description: Gravel highway parking area next to the small lagoon. Picnic tables and bins available but limited shade. 12km SW of Yarck and 11km NE of Yea.

properties.name: Ollies Jumpup Campground
properties.description: Shady rest area next to Dargo River. Toilets and picnic tables available, along with swimming and fishing in the river. Located on Upper Dargo Rd, 12km N of Dargo via Dargo High Plains Rd. Winding dirt road. Signposted.

properties.name: Toolangi Recreational Reserve
properties.description: Shady free camping area in Toolangi next to the creek. Located on Cherrys Ln, N of Healesville-Kinglake Rd. Signposted.

properties.name: Leitchville Travellers Rest Stop
properties.description: Nice, well established overnight parking area. Water available for tank fills.

properties.name: Aysons Reserve
properties.description: Large grassy camp area next to Campaspe River. Permit required. Toilets (bring your own paper) and dump point available, with some shade from trees. There is also a boat ramp for fishing in the river. Located 3km N of Burnewang or 13km S of Rochester. Max stay: 28 days.

properties.name: Twelve Mile Reserve
properties.description: Shady camp area set back from the road on the banks of Goulburn River. Toilets available, please do not wash in the river and take your rubbish with you. A nice area for a spot of fishing or canoeing. Located on Mansfield-Woods Point Road, 9km N of Knockwood or 10km SE of Kevington. Sign out front.

properties.name: Leaghur Spot
properties.description: Picnic and camping area in Leaghur State Park. Picnic tables available, no other facilities. Available in dry weather only. Camping in the park only permitted in the two designated areas. GPS is at signposted entrance to the park. 29km SW of Kerang.

properties.name: Cheynes Bridge
properties.description: Large grassy free camping area next to Macalister River. Toilets, picnic tables and bins available, some shade from trees. Also a nice area for fishing and swimming. 20km S of Licola on Heyfield-Jamieson Rd.

properties.name: Beggs Bend State Forest Camp Area
properties.description: Small and basic area, not far to the river. No facilities. Take your rubbish with you.

properties.name: Y
properties.description: Various sites along the river in the very big park. Quite a few trees, no rubbish bins and no toilets.

properties.name: Lake Ratzcastle Camp Area
properties.description: Very big and remotely located camping area situated by a lake side. There are toilets and solar showers, designated sheltered picnic area and some picnic tables. You can get some privacy, as there is plenty of space and trees.

properties.name: Staceys Bridge Camp Area
properties.description: Level camping area next to Wheeler Creek. Toilets and picnic tables available and plenty of shade. Located 40km S of Corryong on Benambra-Corryong Rd.

properties.name: Yaapeet Beach Campground
properties.description: Free camping in Lake Albacutya Regional Park. Non flush toilets and picnic tables available. Lake is sometimes dry. Dirt road access, may not be good in wet weather. 4km W of Yaapeet via Yaapeet-Kenmare Rd.

properties.name: Sheepyard Flat
properties.description: Free camping on the Howqua River. Toilets and picnic tables available, and plenty of shade. 17km of dirt road to get here from Merrijig.

properties.name: Granthams Bend Camping
properties.description: Large camping area on the edge of the river. Is prone to flooding. No facilities. Not recommended for large vehicle.

properties.name: Christies Beach Campground
properties.description: Large free camp area in Echuca Regional Park next to the Murray River. Drop toilet available but no other facilities so please take your rubbish with you.  The river is accessible via stairs cut in the bank and there is a launching spot for boats. Dry weather access only with a 4WD recommended. 6km E of Echuca.

properties.name: Murrungowar Picnic Rest Area
properties.description: SC and non-SC. Toilets, non-drinkable tap water, picnic tables, fireplaces and sheltered areas.

properties.name: Loch Valley Campground
properties.description: Free camping area on the banks of the Loch River. Toilet, picnic tables and camp fire pits available. Located just off Loch Valley Road, 9km North of Noojee. Mainly sealed road last few hundred meters dirt road. Winding access road but log truck use the road so motor home can access. Great place for families and room for the kids to run / ride around. The Loch creek is only shallow and cold and not for swimming but the kids can play in spots. Has 20+ camp sites plus traffic than the near by falls camp site.

properties.name: Dogs Grave Campground
properties.description: Free bush camping area 35km W of Swifts Creek. Toilets and picnic tables available, no rubbish bins so take all rubbish with you. Access via Upper Livingstone Rd and then Birregun Rd.

properties.name: Schulzes Beach Camp Area
properties.description: Free camp area in Lake Hindmarsh Lake Reserve. Pit toilets available, along with swimming and fishing in the freshwater lake. To get here, take Rainbow-Nhill Rd 28km and turn E (at -36.050704, 141.838029) to get to camp area. Sandy track.

properties.name: Manangatang Travellers Rest
properties.description: Large dirt rest area in the middle of Manangatang. Toilets, showers and rubbish bins available. Donation requested for upkeep. On Wattle St, just N of Mallee Hwy. Max stay: 24hrs.

properties.name: Tarra River Rest Area
properties.description: Basic parking area close to road. Rubbish bins and picnic benches available. Accessible for long vehicles. No toilets. Grassy area to park on.

properties.name: Bemm River Rest Area
properties.description:
500m gravel road in, for SC and non-SC. Toilets, picnic tables, walking track and non-drinkable tap water available.
Day Use Area Only no overnight stays

properties.name: Avon River
properties.description: Shady dirt rest area beside Wimmera Hwy just N of Avon River. Picnic tables and rubbish bins available. 27km W of St. Arnaud.

properties.name: Boolarra Club Hotel
properties.description: Camping available next to the hotel. Check in when you arrive. Toilets available.

properties.name: Koriella Rest Area
properties.description: Small rest area on N side of Maroondah Hwy. Picnic tables and rubbish bins available. Located 6km NW of Alexandra.

properties.name: Hiscocks Crossing
properties.description: Bush camping beside the Crawford River in Crawford River Regional Park. Toilet and picnic tables available. Follow Mill Rd onto The Blvd, travelling W from Hotspur. Dirt road. Route from Greenwald not good for caravans.

properties.name: Tunnel Bend Reserve
properties.description: Camping on the Goulburn River. Toilets and picnic tables available, no bins so please take your rubbish with you. Located 8km S of Kevington on Mansfield-Woods Point Rd.

properties.name: Apex Beach
properties.description: Camping on the banks of the Murray River in Tocumwal Regional Park. Toilets, picnic tables and BBQs available, as well as the river for fishing and swimming (but be aware of strong currents). Turnoff is on W side of Goulburn Valley Hwy, just S of Tocumwal and the Murray River bridge. 4WD recommended.

properties.name: Victoria Falls Camping Area
properties.description: Grassy camping area next to the Victoria River. Toilets and picnic tables available. Turn off is at the SE end of Cobungra, travel 500m to campsite. Dirt road.

properties.name: Picnic Point Camp
properties.description: Camping area by the river in Delatite Arm Reserve. Toilets available, as well as swimming and fishing in the river. To access from Goughs Bay, follow Walsh's Rd W for 10km until you reach the campsite. Dirt road.

properties.name: Western Beach Campground
properties.description: Free camp area on the W banks of Lake Albacutya. Toilets, showers and picnic tables available. Lake is often dry. To get here from Rainbow, travel N and turn W onto Albacutya Rd. Continue on this road until it becomes Western Beach Rd, and follow to camp area.

properties.name: Picnic Point Reserve
properties.description: Shady camp area on the banks of Goulburn River. Toilets available, as well as the river for swimming and fishing. Please take your rubbish with you. Located N of Knockwood, 16km SE of Kevington. Signposted.

properties.name: Greens Campground
properties.description: Large camp rest area in Whroo Historic Reserve. Toilets and lots of shade available. Located 8km S of Rushworth via Nagambie-Rushworth Rd.

properties.name: Wannon Falls Camping
properties.description: Sealed road to campsite. Gas BBQ, toilets, tap water, covered picnic tables with enclosed fire place and walking tracks

properties.name: Toorongo Falls Campground
properties.description:
Large grassy camp area beside the Toorongo River. 

Toilets and picnic tables available, as well as the river for fishing and swimming. 10km NE of Noojee, via Mount Baw Baw Tourist Rd and Toorongo Valley Rd.

properties.name: Edi Cutting Camping Area
properties.description: Free camping next to the King River. Toilets and picnic tables available, river is good for fishing. Located 4km N of King Valley and 11km S of Moyu. Turn off Wangaratta-Whitfield Rd onto dirt road (at -36.663385, 146.419694) and follow down to the river for camping.

properties.name: Heathcote Rest Area
properties.description: Free camp area at S end of Ambers Drive in Heathcote. Sheltered picnic table, no other facilities so SC only. Max stay: 48hrs.

properties.name: Ah Sye's Camping Area
properties.description: Free grassy camping area in forest. Toilets and picnic tables available, as well as river nearby for swimming and fishing. Located on Benambra-Corryong Rd, 30km N of Benambra, not suitable for caravan access from Corryong.

properties.name: Brodies Campground
properties.description: Free camp area in Rocklands Reservoir. No facilities available but good for fishing. To access, turn S off Rocklands-Cherrypool Rd (at -37.222246, 141.995467) and continue S until you reach reservoir camp area. Dirt road.

properties.name: Loch Ard Gorge
properties.description: The Loch Ard Gorge is one of the best-loved stop-off points along the Great Ocean Road. It's situated in the Port Campbell National Park and is just three minutes from the world-famous formation of the Twelve Apostles.

properties.name: Mallacoota's Shady Gully Caravan Park
properties.description: Accommodation including ensuite and standard cabins, luxury cabins and large powered and unpowered sites.

properties.name: Holey Hills Campground
properties.description: Awesome spot on top of the hill with a watchtower and good open camp areas.

properties.name: Bennies Campground
properties.description: Free camp by river drop toilet roads closed seasonally

properties.name: Broughtons Waterhole Camping Area
properties.description: A tranquil spot amongst the trees adjacent to an intermittent waterhole. The shaded picnic area provides a cool respite for the weary traveller or the ever-watchful kangaroo or wallaby.

properties.name: Huon Reserve
properties.description: This is a Free Camping area provided by the local council or community located by the lake. No facilities as toilets are currently under construction.
properties.fees: There is no charge for the use of this facility, so if you are staying at this site we encourage you to help keep it clean and tidy.

properties.name: Border Inn Hotel
properties.description: A small piece of land at the back of a great local bar. Free camping available- $5 for a hot shower in pub- need to check in with the hotel before parking up.

properties.name: Sunny Acres Farm
properties.description:
Sunny Acres Farm is pet friendly camping and farmstay located in country Victoria.
