Bring along your caravan, camper trailer, tent or swag and sleep under the stars at our Shady Acres camping grounds. You will have access to the “Sugar Shack” complete with bbq and cooking facilities and there is also an ensuite for all to use.

Camping (no powered sites – generators welcome)
properties.fees: Adults $10pp per night, Kids aged 7yrs - 15yrs $5pp per night

properties.name: Dollys Creek Campground
properties.description: Bush free camping area next to Moorabool River West Branch

properties.name: Devils Cove Camp Ground
properties.description: Book through VIC Parks , easy access. A little muddy in the wet season.

properties.name: Genoa Falls Track
properties.description:
Genoa Falls is a beautiful waterfall located in the Otway Ranges National Park, Victoria, Australia. It is about 30 meters high and cascades into a large pool below. There is a short walking track that leads to the waterfall, which is suitable for all ages and abilities. The falls are best visited after rain, when the water flow is heavy. However, they are still beautiful to see at any time of year. 

Genoa Falls is a popular spot for swimming, picnicking, and bushwalking. There is also a small camping area located nearby.

properties.name: Angusvale Camping Area
properties.description:
Once you get down the 16km of corrugated dirt road from the Dargo Road, you arrive at the camping ground beside the Mitchell River. There is a large cleared area, enough room for hundreds of campers. There are several composting toilets on site.

The camping area is maintained by the Parks dept and they keep the camping areas mowed and trimmed.  The River can be used for water activities. There are walking tracks into the National Park.  Morning and evening if it's not too busy, kangaroos will come to the camping area to feed on the grass. 

It really is one of the most ideallic places to enjoy a day or a week and relax. No mobile phone coverage at the camping site, (if you go back up the hill a km or two you can get service) and Dargo is the nearest shop & pub for supplies

properties.name: Mackenzie Falls
properties.description:
MacKenzie Falls is one of the largest waterfalls in Victoria and a must-see on your trip to Grampians National Park. It's the only waterfall in the Grampians that flows all year round. 

See the beauty and power of MacKenzie Falls from a variety of lookouts and walks, which start at the carpark and cater to a range of abilities.

properties.name: Sheep Hills Silo Art
properties.description: Sheep Hills Silo Art: A stunning mural of two Indigenous elders and two children, painted by Adnate. The artwork celebrates the richness of the local Indigenous culture and the importance of passing on knowledge to the next generation.

properties.name: Tower Hill Peak Climb
properties.description: The Tower Hill Peak Climb near Belfast Coastal Reserve is an exhilarating adventure in Victoria. Tower Hill is an extinct volcano, and this climb takes you to the summit, offering panoramic views of the surrounding landscape, including the Belfast Coastal Reserve and its picturesque coastline. As you ascend, you'll encounter unique geological features and lush flora. It's an excellent way to immerse yourself in nature, appreciate the region's volcanic history, and enjoy the breathtaking vistas that stretch to the ocean.

properties.name: The Orchard Camp Ground Lake Eildon
properties.description: Beautiful free camp by the side of Lake Eildon/Delatite River. Note: 5km of corrugated dirt road to reach this first site + 5km more to reach other sites.

properties.name: Starlings Gap Camping Area
properties.description: Forest overnighter for bush walkers. Blacksands Rd from the east is well surfaced. Bring everything. No water. Take your rubbish.

properties.name: Tarnagulla Recreation Reserve
properties.description:
Maintained by Loddon Valley shire the Tarnagulla camping ground provides low cost camping for caravanning, motorhomes tents, etc. No powered sites, but clean toilets and hot showers (coin in slot - $1.00 for 3 minutes- uses $1.00 coins only) are available. You can select sites on large open areas around the former sports oval. Plenty of shaded areas. Playground for kids and plenty of play area on the oval. Grass on oval is kept short by a team of kangaroos. Campfires permitted during non-stop restricted times - check with caretaker.
Old reservoir is good for yabbying and fishing (on south boundary of the camping ground. 
Tarnagulla and its surrounds are renowned gold producing areas and is a popular base for prospectors

properties.name: Walpeup Wayside Stop
properties.description: Price list is on the outside of the toilet block but basic powered sites are by $10 donation plus $3 for a hot shower. Please be honest and leave the money in the box provided.
properties.fees: $9 for unpowered site $10 for powered $3 for hot shower $50 for a week

properties.name: Harrop Track Aboriginal Rock Art
properties.description:
The Harrop Track Aboriginal Rock Art is a significant cultural site located in the Grampians National Park, Victoria, Australia. The site is home to over 100 rock art panels, which were created by the Aboriginal people over thousands of years.

The rock art at Harrop Track depicts a variety of subjects, including animals, people, and ceremonial objects. The art is also significant because it provides a record of the Aboriginal people's way of life and their connection to the land.

The Harrop Track Aboriginal Rock Art site is accessible to the public, but it is important to be respectful of the site and the Aboriginal people's culture. Visitors should not touch or damage the rock art, and they should leave no trace of their visit.

properties.name: Chinese Gardens Camp Grounds
properties.description: Check in at the Wahalla General Store

properties.name: Lake Hume
properties.description: A max of 24 hours stay. Really pretty place. No tents

properties.name: Winton Wetlands Reserve
properties.description:
Winton Wetlands Reserve is unique in so many ways. It's spectacular. It's enriching. It's engaging. Above all, it's fun. 

The largest wetlands restoration project in the southern hemisphere, the Winton Wetlands brings people, groups and communities together to renew themselves and the landscape.

properties.name: Tarago Reservoir Park
properties.description: Tarago Reservoir Park offers the perfect setting for a picnic or barbecue with family and friends. The picnic area has sloping lawns set amongst bush settings, with views of the reservoir and surrounding landscapes.

properties.name: Leaghur State Park
properties.description: Leaghur State Park, located in Victoria, Australia, is a nature lover's paradise. This serene wilderness area boasts diverse flora and fauna, tranquil bushwalks, and scenic picnic spots. With its rich Indigenous history and stunning landscapes, it offers a perfect escape for hikers, birdwatchers, and those seeking a peaceful retreat.

properties.name: Cape Conran Coastal Park
properties.description:
Cape Conran Coastal Park, nestled along Victoria's southeast coast in Australia, is a coastal haven of natural beauty. It features pristine beaches, rugged cliffs, and serene estuaries, offering an ideal escape for nature enthusiasts. 

The park is teeming with diverse wildlife and provides numerous hiking, camping, and water-based recreational opportunities. A great park for water activities - enjoy swimming, diving, boating, fishing or rock pooling.

properties.name: Agnes Falls
properties.description:
Hidden within the rolling green hills of the Strzelecki Ranges, the meandering Agnes River cascades over rocks into a deep picturesque gorge. 

At 59 metres, Agnes Falls are the highest single span falls in Victoria. 

Take a short stroll through the Blue Gum Forest to a viewing area overlooking the waterfalls or relax and enjoy a picnic under the shade of tall blue gums on the grassy banks of the Agnes River.

properties.name: Little O'Tools Camp Site
properties.description: Right on the river with pit toilet, a few designated camp sites with fire pits. Great flat sites in a great location, just down from the larger O'Tooles Campsites.

properties.name: Goonans - Toombon State Forest
properties.description:
Primitive campsite with basic facilities. Nice and quiet location away from the main road. 
Access by 4wd advisable

properties.name: Hotel Granya
properties.description:
Hotel Granya is located just 45 minutes drive from Albury.
Featuring a fully licensed bar, bistro, bed & breakfast & backpacker accommodation.
Free camping is also available.
A range of alcohol, hot food &  cold drinks,  ice, a gas refill service, local newspapers.
It's a very convenient stop to relax and enjoy the surrounds. 
We also cater for Groups, Motorcycle and Car clubs.

properties.name: Swing Bridge Campsite
properties.description: Basic campsite alongside the river. Access only from the Eastern side of the bridge. Carp fishing available. Self contained only.

properties.name: Lakes Entrance Lookout
properties.description:
The Lakes Entrance Lookout serves as an ideal launchpad for your discovery of this charming seaside resort town and bustling fishing port. 

Additionally, it's the perfect spot to conclude an exhilarating journey. Ascend to the summit viewpoint to soak in the panoramic vistas of the town's breathtaking lake shores, coastal heathlands, and the boundless expanse of the cerulean Bass Strait on the horizon.

properties.name: Fitzroy River Reserve
properties.description: Flat camping area relatively close to the ocean (200m). There is a small camping fee in peak times.

properties.name: McMenzie River Rainforest Walk
properties.description:
The McKenzie River Rainforest Walk is a 1-kilometre loop walk located in the Bemm River Scenic Reserve in Victoria, Australia.The walk is a mixture of sealed pathways, boardwalks, and two swing bridges over the picturesque McKenzie River.

The walk offers stunning views of the surrounding riparian forest from within the canopy.

properties.name: Sugarbush Lodge and Apartments
properties.description: Nestled amongst the snow gums just 400 metres from the centre of Mt Buller, Sugarbush Lodge and Apartments offers Mt Buller accommodation cheap enough to offer great value for money but still including everything you will need to make the most of Mount Buller snow and the legendary Buller nightlife.

properties.name: Wills Bend - River Murray Reserve
properties.description: This is a popular camping destination located close to town. It has good facilities and offers fantastic walking, fishing, swimming and water sports opportunities. The campsites are dispersed along the river, mainly level and grassy with some shade available.

properties.name: Willow Park Rest Area at Rosedale
properties.description: This large overnighter with good amenities is located just off the highway, on the banks of the river. There is some shade and a few pleasant walking tracks around. Suitable for big rigs with maximum stay of 36hrs. Gold coin donation requested.

properties.name: Talbotville Campground
properties.description: This dispersed and grassy campsite is located on the bank of Crooked River, in the Grant Historic Area. It is large and open, with a few trees scattered here and there. It is a very popular campsite, due to its accessibility and convenient location for exploring Blue Rag Range and Billy Goats Bluff Track. A 4WD is strongly recommended.

properties.name: Snowy River Rest Area No 5
properties.description: This large, grassy camping area is located off the road, by the Snowy River. It has no facilities, except for rubbish bins, however it offers scenic views and great fishing. Suitable for any size rigs with maximum stay of 48hrs.

properties.name: Mount Korong Scenic Reserve Camping Area
properties.description: This beautiful camping area with no amenities, except for picnic tables, is located in the Mount Korong Scenic Reserve, approx. 6km from the highway. There is a good shade and it offers scenic views.

properties.name: Moscow Villa Hut Camp Area
properties.description: Picturesque campground located up in the mountains, but easily accessible by all vehicles. The facilities are basic (long drop toilet), but shade and space are plentiful. There are around 5 sites to choose from located north and south of the creek.

properties.name: Merringtons Flat - Thomson State Forest
properties.description: This is a large, flat and open bush campground with no facilities. It's is located in a state forest not too far from the highway and is usually busy with 4WD and motorbike aficionados. There are many scenic trails available around, both for drivers and hikers. 4WD access only.

properties.name: McMillans Camp - Murchison State Forest
properties.description: This campground is located by the Goulburn River, just off the highway. It's mainly level and has no amenities. There is plenty of shade coming from big trees and the traffic noise is limited. This stretch of the river is very scenic and good for fishing.

properties.name: McKinnons Point - Briagolong State Forest
properties.description: This is a basic riverside campground with no facilities. It is situated in Briagolong State Forest and is rich in bird life. There are many walking trails available in the area, incl. short to multi-day treks. This campsite is a short distance away from Blue Pool, which offers great swimming opportunities. Access with 4WD is recommended.

properties.name: Lake Ratzcastle Camping Area
properties.description: Beautiful, small camping area with fantastic facilities, located on the bank of the lake in a very peaceful surrounding. It offers scenic views and there is a fishing spot. It's popular and easily accessible.

properties.name: Kendalls Camping Area
properties.description: These bush camps with basic amenities are situated in a state forest, along the western bank of the Rubicon River. Campsite A and B are situated a short walk away from each other and are very similar. They are both level and shaded, and can be accessed by an unsealed track, just off Rubicon Rd. They offer a selection of activities, incl. mountain biking, hiking, fishing, swimming and 4WD exploring. Closed from Queens Birthday weekend until Melbourne Cup Weekend.

properties.name: Karri Track Camping Area - Paddys Ranges State Park
properties.description: This dispersed campground consists of 3 level sites that are well cleared of all scrub. It has basic facilities (long drop toilets) and is picturesquely located among some bush, well off the main road. The wildlife in this area is fantastic and it is home to some 130+ species of native birds. There are plenty of walking tracks to follow and some gold mining relics to explore, too.

properties.name: Henrys Camping Area - Rocklands State Forest
properties.description: This is a remote riverside bush camp with no facilities. Once you arrive at the GPS location, any track will take you to the river bank, just aim at the southernmost corner of the Reservoir. Glenelg River is an attractive destination for fishing and swimming. 4WD only.

properties.name: Haunted Stream Camping Area
properties.description: This area features a selection of different campgrounds scattered along the creek. It has no facilities, however, it provides creek access, large grassy sites and plenty of shade. Swimming, fishing and 4WD exploring are allowed here. It is best to access any campground in this area by 4x4 vehicles.

properties.name: Greens Lake Recreation Reserve
properties.description: This spacious camping area with good amenities is located on the bank of the Greens Lake, close to Green Lake Rd. There is a boat ramp, various fishing spot aa well as non-potable water - you'll need a tap key to open it. Suitable for big rigs.

properties.name: Grannys Flat Camping Reserve
properties.description: This scenic camping area with good amenities is located in a State Forest, on the bank of the river. Fishing and swimming are permitted here and the site has access to a few walking tracks. Easily accessible by all vehicles.

properties.name: Glenpatrick Reserve
properties.description: This spacious rest area with good facilities is located just off the road. It offers scenic views, great wildlife and it's suitable for big rigs. Please make sure to take your rubbish with you. Donations are appreciated.

properties.name: Fulham Streamside Reserve
properties.description: This scenic bush campground with no facilities is located along the river. It offers postcard views, a few walking tracks and good fishing. Suitable for camper trailers and motorhomes. Closed in winter.

properties.name: Lake Bolac Foreshore
properties.description: Lake Bolac Foreshore offers beach side camping. Toilets and hot showers are available. Showers are at Picnic Point, towards the end of the main beach. Fees will be collected by the patrolling rangers.

properties.name: Lake Tooliorook
properties.description: Lake Tooliorook is a campground nestled amongst trees with unpowered sites, toilets and showers. Call for booking and more information.
properties.fees: AUD $10 Adult; Kids under 16 are free.

properties.name: Donald Lakeside Caravan Park
properties.description: Donald Lakeside Caravan Park offers a range of accommodation from cabins to powered and unpowered sites for caravans. An outdoor BBQ area and laundry facilities are available. Call to book or for enquiries.

properties.name: Geelong Showground
properties.description: Geelong Showgrounds has powered sites with toilets and showers.

properties.name: Newbridge Recreation Reserve
properties.description: Newbridge Recreation Reserve provides easily accessed, centrally located campsites with hot showers, and flush toilets. See the General Store and Newbridge Hotel to obtain a camping permit and shower tokens.

properties.name: Four Mile Beach Camping Ground
properties.description: Four Mile Beach Camping Ground is around Lake Hindmarsh Lake Reserve, offering good basic facilities with flush toilets. Fees apply, call for more information. A few other areas around the lake provide free camping spots with pit toilets.

properties.name: Glenpatrick Reserve
properties.description: Glenpatrick Reserve camping area provides sites for tents, caravans and long rigs. Facilities include toilets, BBQ, fireplace, and picnic tables. Pets are allowed. Donations are requested.

properties.name: Lockington Travellers Stopover
properties.description: Lockington Travellers Stopover is a community run rest stop. There are 8 powered sites suitable for caravans, camper trailers and motorhomes. Facilities include toilets, children's playground, BBQ, toilets, showers, water and dump point. Dogs are allowed.

properties.name: Mallee Bush Retreat
properties.description: Mallee Bush Retreat offers a range of accomodation. There are powered sites available for a small fee and free camping is allowed along the Lake. Bookings can be made by phone.

properties.name: Tolmie Recreation Reserve
properties.description: Tolmie Recreation Reserve provides bush camping. Facilities include fire pits, picnic shelter, tables and toilet. You will need to bring self-sufficient.

properties.name: Johnny Mullagh Park
properties.description: Situated on the Glenelg River, Johnny Mullagh Park offers an overnight rest area for tents, caravans and large rigs. There are 4 powered sites available. Facilities include  amenitites block, BBQ, and playground. Fees can be paid at the General store.

properties.name: Loch Memorial Reserve
properties.description: Tel. 0492911213 for bookings. Please call between 8am and 7 pm.

properties.name: Beulah Caravan Park
properties.description: Located on the banks of Yarriambiack Creek, Beulah Caravan Park offers powered and non-powered sites suitable for tents, motorhomes, and caravans. Facilities include BBQ, playground, amenitites block, bins and grassed recreation area. In the area you can enjoy the walking tracks, bird watching and public swimming pool.

properties.name: St Arnaud Caravan Park
properties.description: St Arnaud Caravan Park provides powered and unpowered sites for tents, caravans and long rigs, There are also cabins for hire. Facilities include toilets, showers, drinking water, BBQ, laundromat and mobile phone coverage. There is a local swimming pool, shops and Sporting Club in walking distance.  Pets are welcome.

properties.name: Cavendish Recreation Reserve
properties.description: Cavendish Recreation Reserve campground offers 12 powered and unpowered sites suitable for tents, caravans, motorhomes and camper trailers. Facilities include toilets, wood BBQ, and picnic tables. Fires are allowed. You will need to bring your own wood. Local attractions include swimming, fishing, canoeing and kayaking. There is a caretaker on site.
properties.fees: AUD $6 per night (un-powered) and extra $10 for power

properties.name: Wodonga Showgrounds
properties.description:
Wodonga Showgrounds offers a small camping area with 8 powered sites. Facilities include toilets, water and showers. There is a maximum stay of 30 days.
All sites have access to their own power and water.
Please note that only caravans, campervans and motorhomes are permitted to stay at the Wodonga Show Society Caravan Park.
There are no unpowered sites and tents are not permitted.

properties.name: Nyah Recreation Reserve
properties.description: Located on the banks of the Murray River, Nyah Recreation Reserve camping area offers sites for tents, caravans and large rigs. Facilities include toilets, fireplace, dump station and picnic tables.  Attractions include walking tracks, and bird watching opportunities. There is a maximum stay of seven days.

properties.name: Wooroonook Lake
properties.description: Wooroonook Lake camping area provides powered and non powered sites, suitable for large caravans and motorhomes. Facilities include toilets, showers, water, mobile phone service, BBQ and picnic tables. In the area you can enjoy swimming, canoeing, kayaking and fishing. Bookings can be made at the campsite through self serve.
properties.fees: AUD $15 for powered sites $5 for non-powered sites

properties.name: Serviceton Recreational Reserve
properties.description: Serviceton Recreational Reserve Camping Ground offers overnight camping with unpowerd sites and 8 powered sites suitable for caravans and big rigs. Facilites include toilets, showers, games room, and tennis court. Bore water is available but is not sutiable for drinking.
properties.fees: AUD $15 per powered sites AUD $10 unpowered site

properties.name: Big Hill Campground
properties.description: Big Hill Track campground is a bushland open grassy area with unpowered sites suitable for tents, caravans or camper trailers. Facilities include pit toilets and communal fireplaces. You will need to be self-sufficient with water and firewood.

properties.name: Freemans Camp - Tallarook State Forest
properties.description: This recently upgraded site is the only campground in the Tallarook state forest that has toilet facilities. It features several grassy and sloping sites with a few level areas suitable for bigger vehicles. It is a popular 4WD and motor bike destination, due to a variety of trails around. Easily accessible by all vehicles.

properties.name: Elizabeth Park
properties.description: A large, grassy and open area situated on Western Highway in front of McDonald's. There are no amenities and 24hrs limit applies.

properties.name: Chinamans Camp Area - Mt Cole State Forest
properties.description: This is a scenically located and easily accessible campsite with basic amenities, including a shelter. It offers plenty of short and long walks in the area and it’s also a great gateway to Pyrenees Wine District and the Grampians. This site is popular with tourist, hikers and horse riders alike.

properties.name: Chinamans Bend - Murray River Reserve
properties.description: This spacious and grassy bush camp is located on the banks of the Murray River, just 1km away from Yarrawonga. It has no amenities, but non-potable water is available.

properties.name: Carney Creek Camp Area - Briagolong State Forest
properties.description: Small grassy area located off the main road by a creek. It's shaded and provides shelter from the traffic noise. There are no facilities and 4WD is recommended.

properties.name: Burnt Bridge Camp Area - Lower Big River
properties.description: This riverside campground is located well off the road, but can be easily accessed by a conventional vehicle. There are toilets and picnic tables, as well as shade and fire pits. The Big River - dubbed by heritage authorities 'the scenic heart of the forested valley' - provides great fishing.

properties.name: Bulldog Flat Camp Area - Lower Big River
properties.description: Riverside campground with plenty of space for vehicles of any size. It's located close by the main road, making it a popular fishing destination for locals. There are no amenities here.

properties.name: Black Snake Creek Camping Area
properties.description: Large riverside camp ground with grassy level surface and good facilities. It's located off the beaten track at the junction of two rivers, which makes it an interesting fishing, swimming and kayaking destination. A gateway to many 4WD tracks

properties.name: Beveridges Station Camping Area
properties.description: Spacious and open campground with stunning mountain views. Access with 4x4 vehicles only via narrow and windy roads. No facilities here.

properties.name: Barkly River Camping Area
properties.description: A beautifully located riverside campground positioned on both sides of the bridge. The site's surface is level and grassy with mountain river views stretching in all directions. 4x4 vehicles are strongly recommended, as access road is steep and narrow.

properties.name: Andersons Garden - Mt Disappointment State Forest
properties.description: Large creak-side camping with well-maintained facilities and breathtaking views. It's easy to access this spot with any vehicle and the campsite is popular with campers, bikers and horse riders alike.

properties.name: Andersons Beach - Murchison State Forest
properties.description: Shaded and relatively flat campsite located just by the river. Access road is in a good condition and views are spectacular. There are no facilities available.

properties.name: Snowy River Bend Rest Area
properties.description: On roadside, SC only, 48 hours max stay. Dogs on leash are okay. No fires. Picnic tables and cell reception.

properties.name: Reedy Arm Area
properties.description: This beautiful little spot has direct access to the water. There are many boats around for fishing. Take the gravel road Reedy Arm No.2 TK to the very end. 4WD recommended. Only for SC vehicles as there are no facilities. The area is very steep, there are only 2 - 4 level spots.

properties.name: Lochiel Jane Picnic Area
properties.description: 5km of dirt road, picnic tables, fire places. SC only.

properties.name: Turtons Creek Falls Campground
properties.description: Beautiful little campground right at the river. Very quiet place with nice walks to explore the forest. Falls are 2km away. No toilet facilities, no rubbish bins. SC only. Picnic table available. 5km of narrow and windy gravel road to get here. Rocks and trees might be in your way. Beautiful drive to Turtons Creek. No cell reception.

properties.name: Sea Lake Caravan Park
properties.description: Low cost campsite, $15 for 1 person powered, $20 for 2 person powered, $15 for 2 person unpowered

properties.name: Spence Bend Camp Area
properties.description: Free overnight campsite on the banks of the Murray River. 300 metres of dirt road, pick one of many spots in the area.

properties.name: Wood Wood Rest Area
properties.description: Beautiful free campsite along the Murray River. To drive in you can enter at the back of the rest area where the toilets are, then it's a 300 metre drive on a dirt road. Multiple sites.

properties.name: Nyah-Vinifera Park Camp Area No.2
properties.description: Another beautiful campsite available to self-contained campervans. 1km of dirt road to get here.

properties.name: Forges Beach No.2 Camp Area
properties.description: Drive down Forges Pump Roas (near the sign for Olive Oil cafe). Dirt road to get here. Large parking area on the edge of the river.

properties.name: Highway Rest Area
properties.description: Well established rest area adjacent to the highway with many facilities, including multiple water taps.

properties.name: Goulburn River Rest Area
properties.description: Nice parking area on the edge of Goulburn River. Site is away from the road so no traffic noise. No facilities.

properties.name: Boolarra Apex Park
properties.description: Large grassy camping spot on the banks of Morwell River. Picnic tables and shade available. Located on Morwell River Rd, 22km E of Mirboo North via Boolarra-Mirboo N Rd.

properties.name: Blue Range Creek Campground
properties.description: Free grassy camp area next to the creek. Toilets and picnic tables available, lots of shade. 15km N of Mansfield via via Mansfield-Whitfield Rd. 4km of dirt road.

properties.name: Loddon Floodway
properties.description: Free camping on the Murray River. No facilities, but swimming and fishing in the river and plenty of shade. 3km of dirt road, small vehicles only. 19km SE of Swan Hill via Pental Island Rd.

properties.name: Murray-Kulkyne Park Camping
properties.description: Beautiful campsite on a large sweeping bend of the river. 3km of rutted gravel road to get here. No facilities.

properties.name: Cronomby Tanks
properties.description: Free camping area by the pond in Woomelong. Picnic tables available, and you can try your hand at fishing in the pond. SC only. Located just off Sunraysia Hwy on Cronomby Tanks Rd. Max stay: 24hrs.

properties.name: Scotts Reserve
properties.description: Large free camping area next to Goulburn River. Toilets and sheltered picnic tables available. River is nice for swimming on hot days. Located on Mansfield-Woods Point Rd, 3km NW of Woods Point. Dirt road.

properties.name: Edi Turnoff Rest Area
properties.description: Shady free camping area next to King River. Toilets and picnic tables available. Camp in permitted areas only, no generators allowed. 9km SE of Moyhu or 6km N of King Valley.

properties.name: Tullaroop Creek Camp
properties.description: Shady grass camping spot next to Tallaroop Creek. No facilities. 6km E of Havelock on Havelock-Baringhup Rd.

properties.name: AH Youngs Camping Area
properties.description: Large grassy camping area next to Bucklands River. Toilets available along with the river for swimming and fishing. 17km S of Porepunkah via Buckland Valley Rd. Dirt road.

properties.name: Barmah Lakes Campground
properties.description: Shady camp area next to the lake in Barmah National Park. Toilets and picnic tables available. Also great area for swimming, fishing and canoeing. 10km N of Barmah via Boundary Track.

properties.name: Doctors Creek Reserve
properties.description: Large grassy camping area next to Goulburn River. Toilets and picnic tables for use and river available for swimming and fishing. Located on Mansfield-Woods Point Rd, 5km S of Jamieson. Sign out front.

properties.name: Burrowye Reserve Camping Area
properties.description: Large camping area located on the bank of the Murray River, easily accessible via a dirt track. There are plenty of camping spots, shaded and sunny areas and enough privacy, but no amenities. The surface is level. Located just off Murray River Rd, 85km NE of Albury.

properties.name: Dead River Beach
properties.description: Spacious and airy bush camp located right beside the river in Murray River Reserve. It's spread out over a large area and features several sites available for overnight stays. You have a choice of setting up your camp somewhere on a clearing or pitching a tent on an enormous sandy beach. Easily accessible by any vehicle, mainly level. There are toilets and lots of shade available. You can also swim and fish here. 9km NE of Koonoomoo via Cobram-Koonoomoo Rd and Racecourse Rd.

properties.name: Brightlight Saddle Rest Area
properties.description: Simple dirt rest area on Princes Hwy. Picnic tables available and some shade from trees. 20km W of Cann River or 17km NE of Bellbird Creek.

properties.name: Dargile Reserve
properties.description: Shady picnic and camping area on Plantation Rd. Compost toilets and sheltered picnic tables available. 10km N of Heathcote via N Cost Rd, some dirt road.

properties.name: Yupperchair Park Area
properties.description: Rest area on Glenelg Highway just E of Nine Mile Creek bridge. Picnic tables and rubbish bins available with some shade from large trees. 5km W of Glenthompson or 13km E of Dunkeld.

properties.name: Glendinning Campground
properties.description: Free grassy camping on the banks of Rocklands Reservoir. Drop toilets and picnic tables available, and plenty of shade from trees. A great place to swim, fish and break out your canoe. 24km SE of Balmoral via Natimuk-Hamilton Rd and Glendinning Rd.

properties.name: King Parrot Creek Rest Area
properties.description: Free camp area next to the creek, just off the highway S of the bridge. Picnic tables available and it's a good area for fishing. Some shade from trees. 7km SE of Trawool or 8.5km NW of Homewood.

properties.name: Teddington Reservoir
properties.description: Shady free camp area next to the reservoir in Kara Kara National Park. Toilets and picnic tables available. Popular area for fishing but no swimming allowed. 6.5km SW of Stuart Mill via Teddington Rd.

properties.name: Cottontree Creek Campground
properties.description: Free picnic and camping area in Mt Granya State Park next to the creek. Toilet and picnic table available. Some shade. Located 1.5km SW of Granya via Webbs Ln (dirt road).

properties.name: James Camping Reserve
properties.description: Small camping area in Strathbogie Ranges State Forest next to Black Charlies Creek. Toilets and picnic tables available, please take your rubbish with you. River provides fresh water but boil before drinking. Located 13km SW of Swanpool via Lima E Rd. Dirt road.

properties.name: Tom Mitchell Reserve Rest Area
properties.description: Popular free rest stop located just off Murray Valley Hwy. Toilets, picnic tables and BBQ facilities available. Some shade from trees. On Avondale Rd, 40km E of Tallangatta or 40km W of Corryong.

properties.name: Moliagul Rest Area
properties.description: Large roadside camping area at the S end of Moliagul. Toilets, picnic table, rubbish bins and BBQ available. Some shade from trees. On Dunolly Rd.

properties.name: C.R.B Campground
properties.description: Large grassy camp area next to Cobungra River in Alpine National Park. Toilets, picnic tables and shade available, along with swimming and fishing. Located on Omeo Hwy, 27km N of Omeo. Signposted.

properties.name: The Glasshouse Camping Area Lake Tyers Forest Reserve
properties.description: This spacious campground is located right at Lake Tyres. There are no facilities available, only fire places. Make sure to take your garbage home. Follow the gravel road to the very end (it's about 9km and accessible for 2WD also). SC only.

properties.name: 8 Mile Campground
properties.description: Large grassy camp area next to Howqua River in Alpine National Park. Toilets available and you can swim and fish in the river. 29 km SE of Merrijig via Howqua Hills Rd. Dirt road to get here, small vehicles only.

properties.name: Nyah-Vinifera Park State Forest Camping Area
properties.description: Camp Area on the road between Nyah and Wood Wood. Access via Byrnes road, follow the River signs. Dirt road, only by dry weather. Various campsites along the river. No facilities.

properties.name: Gunbower State Forest
properties.description: Large bush camping site in Murray River Reserve. Toilets and picnic tables available and plenty of shade. River is good for fishing.  2.5 km SE of Koondrook.

properties.name: Burned Bridge Reserve
properties.description: Parking area in the forest, right next to the highway. Picnic benches available, no toilets or rubbish bins.

properties.name: Burnt Creek
properties.description: Gravel rest area beside Western Hwy. Picnic tables, no bins and shade from trees available. 8km SW of Horsham.

properties.name: McKillop Bridge Campground
properties.description: Free bush camping in Snowy River National Park. Non-flush toilets, picnic tables and some shade from trees available. Tight winding dirt road not suitable for caravans. 122km SW of Bombala via Delegate Rd and McKillops Rd. Signposted.

properties.name: Lower Ovens Camp Area
properties.description: Nice campsite located jsut off the roadside No facilities available.

properties.name: Happy Jacks Reserve
properties.description: Large grassy parking area, South of Lockwood South. Find a spot and park up. Short walk to the toilets.

properties.name: Little Toms Beach
properties.description: Basic camping area on the banks of Murray River in Cobram Regional Park. No facilities but swimming and fishing available in the river. Access to camp area via Wondah St at N end of Cobram. Signposted.

properties.name: Fergusons Campground
properties.description: Free bush camp area in Rocklands State Forest next to the river. Toilets and picnic table available, as well as a popular boat ramp. 10km NW of Henty Hwy, via Gartons Rd and Shilcocks Rd.

properties.name: Kings Billabong Reserve
properties.description: Free bush camping area next to Kings Billabong. Great area for fishing, canoeing and bushwalking. At E end of Irymple.

properties.name: Pigs Point Reserve
properties.description: Large grassy camping area located just off Omeo Hwy. Next to Mitta Mitta River where you can swim and fish. Toilets, picnic tables, bins and BBQs available. 14km SE of Tallangatta, signposted from road.

properties.name: Langi Ghiran Picnic and Camping Area Langi Ghiran State Park
properties.description: Located in Langi Ghiran State Park, this campsite is remote and has an excellent access to various walks and nature trails. The camp area is spacious and shaded, the abundance of trees can provide some privacy. There are long drop toilets, rubbish bins, fire and BBQ areas as well as picnic tables. No animals are allowed.

properties.name: Wenhams Camp
properties.description: Simple camp area in Warby-Ovens National Park. Pit toilets and BBQs available. Large groups must contact the Ranger before using the camping areas. Dirt road access, small vehicles only. 16km SW of Waldara via Wangandary Rd and Booth Rd. Signposted out front.

properties.name: Stevenson Falls Camping Reserve Great Otway State Park
properties.description: 5km long windy gravel road to campsite. SC and non-SC allowed, dogs are okay, there is a walking track to falls, fireplaces and toilets.

properties.name: Lightning Creek Camping and Picnic Area
properties.description: Highway rest area adjacent to the creek. Toilets and picnic tables available. 20km S of Mitta Mitta on the Omeo Hwy.

properties.name: English's Bridge
properties.description: Camping area on the banks of the Campaspe River. Picnic tables and fireplaces available and lots of shade from trees. Located on Englishs Rd, 5.5km E of Goornong.

properties.name: Running Creek Campground
properties.description: Free camping area on the banks of the Howqua River. Toilets available, no bins so please take you rubbish with you. Fresh water available from river but probably best to boil before drinking. To get here, take Howqua River Road for 8km E from turn off on Mansfield-Woods Rd (-37.223038, 146.165880) to get to campsite. Dirt road, steep in places.

properties.name: Lochiel Rest Area
properties.description: Free sealed rest area located just off Western Hwy. Lots of space with toilets, picnic tables and bins available. 41km NW of Horsham.

properties.name: Neils Reserve
properties.description: Free camping area next to the Murray River. Picnic tables, no other facilities but you can swim and fish in the river. To access these campsites take dirt road turn off on Murray River Rd. 16km NW of Tintaldra.

properties.name: Psyche Bends
properties.description: Shady free camp area on the Murray River. Picnic tables and BBQs available. Camp area is 15km SE of Mildura, via Calder Hwy and McCracken St.

properties.name: Reeves Beach Coastal Reserve
properties.description: This camping ground is located right behind the dunes, there is a nice little track right to the beach (2min walk). Toilet available, fires allowed (following the announced rules). No water and no rubbish bins. There are several spots to park your car or set up a tent, but it might still be crowded in season or on weekends. The last 3km are gravel road, but smooth to drive even with bigger vans.

properties.name: Forges Beach No.1 Camp
properties.description: Drive down Forges Pump Roas (near the sign for Olive Oil cafe). Dirt road to get here. Large parking area on the edge of the river. There is a second campsite nearby, however this one is better.

properties.name: Lake Walpeup Reserve
properties.description: Free camp area on the banks of Walpeup Lake, however lake is often dry. Picnic tables and lots of shelter available. Located 17km SE of Walpeup via Hopetoun-Walpeup Rd and Walpeup Lake Rd. 6km dirt road.

properties.name: Gibbo River Bush Camping
properties.description: Free shady camp area next to Gibbo River. Picnic tables available, no other facilities except the river for fishing. Narrow road so not good for large caravans. Located on Benambra-Omeo Rd, 50km N of Omeo.

properties.name: Bourkes Bend No 3
properties.description: Large free camp area in Murray River Reserve. No facilities but some shade and swimming and fishing in the river available. Please take your rubbish with you. To access, take Bourkes Bend Track 3.5km N of Murray Valley Hwy.

properties.name: Butts Reserve Camping Area
properties.description: SC and non-SC. Toilets, picnic tables, fire places and water from tap.

properties.name: Meyers Flat Campsite
properties.description: Shady grass camp area next to Wombat Creek. Toilets and picnic tables available, as well as the river for swimming and fishing. 13km S of Dargo on Dargo Rd.

properties.name: Flour Bag Creek Reserve
properties.description: Shady free camping area next to Goulburn River. Toilets available, no other facilities so please take your rubbish with you. Located on Mansfield-Woods Point Rd, 10km N of Knockwood or 10km E of Kevington.

properties.name: Hunts Bridge Camping Area Lal Lal State Forest
properties.description: Spacious and remotely located site consisting of two levels - both are dedicated for camping. properties.name: Griffiths Island Lighthouse
properties.description: Griffiths Island Lighthouse is a historic lighthouse located on Griffiths Island, Port Fairy, Victoria. It was built in 1859 to guide ships into the Port Fairy harbor, which was an important trading port for western Victoria at the time. The lighthouse is made of bluestone and is 28 meters tall. It has a focal plane of 30 meters and a range of 27 nautical miles. The lighthouse was automated in 1954 and the last lighthouse keeper left the island in 1960. Today, the lighthouse is open to the public and visitors can climb to the top for stunning views of Port Fairy, the harbor, and the surrounding coastline.

properties.name: Cape Nelson Lighthouse
properties.description:
Cape Nelson Lighthouse is a historic lighthouse located on Cape Nelson, the southernmost point of the Australian mainland. It is situated approximately 35 kilometres south of Portland, Victoria. The lighthouse was built in 1872 to warn ships of the dangerous coastline and to guide them safely into Portland Harbor.

The lighthouse is a 34-meter-tall stone tower that is painted white. It has a black lantern room on top that houses a powerful light that can be seen for up to 30 nautical miles. The lighthouse is also equipped with a siren that is used to warn ships of foggy conditions.

properties.name: Trentham Falls

Trentham Falls is one of Victoria's most popular waterfalls, located in the Trentham Falls Reserve, about 120 kilometres north of Melbourne, Australia. The falls cascade over three tiers, with a total drop of 32 metres, into a natural pool at the bottom.

The falls are most impressive after heavy rain, when the water cascades over the rocks with a thunderous roar. However, the falls are still beautiful to see even in drier weather.

properties.name: Point Danger Gannet Colony
properties.description:
Point Danger Gannet Colony is a popular tourist destination in Victoria, Australia. It is the only mainland colony of Australasian Gannets in Australia, and is home to over 6000 pairs of birds. The colony is located on Lawrence Rocks, a small island just off the coast of Portland.

The best time to visit Point Danger Gannet Colony is during the breeding season, which runs from July to April. During this time, the birds are nesting and raising their young. Visitors can watch the gannets from a viewing platform on the mainland, or take a boat tour to get a closer look.

properties.name: Petrified Forest
properties.description:
The Petrified Forest at Cape Bridgewater, Victoria, Australia is a unique and fascinating geological feature. Contrary to its name, the forest is not actually a collection of petrified trees. Instead, it is a series of hollow limestone tubes, known as solution pipes, that have been eroded by millions of years of rainfall.

The solution pipes formed when rainwater seeped through the limestone, dissolving it and creating cavities. Over time, the cavities filled with sand and sediment, which hardened into limestone tubes. The tubes are typically around 3 meters high, but some can be as tall as 20 meters.

1.5km, 1 hr return No bushwalking experience required.

The track winds its way steeply up the side of the valley and rewards the walker with beautiful views over Bright and upt the Ovens River towards Porepunkah.  Return on the same track.    Please note there is no access to McFadyens Lane via Zivan Court.

properties.name: Canyon Walk
properties.description:
This Family Friendly walk suits all ages and abilities.
No bushwalking experience is required as it is on a formed track but there are a few obstacles, short steep hills and occasional steps. It is clearly sign posted.

Starting from Howitt Park head towards the Star Road bridge. The track on the northern bank of the Ovens River has steep steps and may be difficult for people with limited mobility. The track on the southern bank from Howitt Park to Canyon Lane is sealed and wheelchair friendly (Grade 1). For a longer loop, continue past the two suspension bridges to the railway bridge and return along the Murray to Mountains Rail Trail.

Otherwise, cross either of the suspension bridges to create a short or long loop. The short loop is easy and accessible for prams. Interpretive signs highlight the local gold mining history of this area. This walk takes you past a small canyon carved by the Ovens River and water races dug by early miners. Keep an eye out for birdlife and wildflowers especially in spring.

Grade: Easy
Distance: 3km
Time: 1.5 hours, return

properties.name: Rubicon Falls Walk
properties.description:
Located in the stunning Rubicon Valley Historic Area, the Rubicon Falls walk starts at the Rubicon Hydro Power Station.

On the right of the power station, follow the Rubicon River Road (service access track only) for approximately 3.7km upwards through the steep sided valley which follows the river and passes Rubicon Falls Power Station on your right.

The 40m high Rubicon Falls comes into view as you climb higher up the road and viewing is restricted to the elevated roadside due to the harsh inaccessible terrain. Nevertheless it's definitely worth the hike.

You can continue up the road even further to Rubicon Falls Dam or combine it into a longer walk and do the circuit to Royston Power Station and the 15,000 ft Siphon Bridge.

properties.name: Power's Lookout
properties.description:
Situated along the Mansfield‐Whitfield Road, Powers Lookout Scenic Reserve provides sweeping panoramas of the surrounding mountain and valley landscape. Just a short drive from Whitfield, the reserve is very popular for day trippers. Visit for magnificent views, walks to suit all abilities, and a unique link to Australian bush ranger history.

This rocky escarpment high above the King Valley was the hideout of Harry Power, a notorious but 'gentlemanly' bushranger of the 1860s. Power reputedly befriended a young Ned Kelly before leading him into a life of crime from which there appeared to be no turning back. On the run from the law for 8 years, Power used the location of the reserve as a hideout and vantage point. Nevertheless, it was here that he was eventually captured by police.

Today, Powers Lookout provides day visitors with a beautiful view of the King Valley, as well as opportunities to spot some of the area's iconic wildlife including Superb Lyrebirds and Wedge-Tailed Eagles.

properties.description:
Climb up through stringybark and mountain ash forest to four of Marysville's best lookouts for spectacular views across Marysville, the Cathedral Range State Park and Steavenson Falls.

The most challenging trail in the area, the Keppel Lookout Trail is fairly uneven and steep in places. Wear sturdy footwear and carry water and snacks.

Start the trail from the car park on Falls Road. Follow the trail across Robertson Gully before climbing up to Keppel Lookout, around the ridge passing Oxlee and De La Rue lookouts, and to the top of Steavenson Falls. Descend to the base of Steavenson Falls and follow the Tree Fern Gully Trail.

Note: the car park on Falls Road can also be accessed by walking two kilometres along the Tree Fern Gully Trail from Marysville.

properties.name: Pink Lakes Trail and Murray Sunset
properties.description:
Murray-Sunset National Park, in Victoria's far north-west corner, is in one of the few remaining semi-arid regions in the world where the environment is relatively untouched. With its wide open landscapes, breathtaking sunsets and starry nights, its vastness and isolation will take more than a day to explore.

This is a great park for four wheel drive touring, bushwalking and camping.

The Pink Lakes are picturesque at most times of year, changing in colour from a deep pink to a glistening white. There are excellent walking tracks in the Pink Lakes area, along with a campground.

A great walk to do is the Pink Lakes Trail. 

Begin at the Pink Lakes picnic area and discover why Victoria's second largest national park is so popular. Four of the park's lakes – Crosbie, Becking, Kenyon and Hardy – turn a vivid pink. This effect is caused by the release of a red pigment called carotene by algae in the water. The brilliant colour is best viewed at dawn, in the late afternoon or under a cloudy sky.

The huge flatlands of Murray-Sunset National Park also provide refuge for some unusual plants and animals. It is home to Victoria's largest flower, the Murray lily and Australia's rarest bird, the black-eared miner. Wander through this untouched wilderness and find a diversity of habitats, including Murray River billabongs, wetlands, woodlands, semiarid sand dunes and salt pans.

properties.name: Cape Woolamai Walk
properties.description:
Cape Woolamai, the highest point on Phillip Island, offers spectacular coastal views and is home for up to a million shearwaters between October and April each year. This area is a hiker's delight with an array of walks to choose from, all offering breathtaking views and scenery!

From Cape Woolamai Beach car park, walk onto the beach, turn left, follow the beach for approximately 1km, take stairs up to clifftop to loop walks. The track offers stunning views and takes you past the Instagram worthy, pinnacles lookout. As you follow the track to the beacon, Phillip Island’s highest point, enjoy the 360-degree views on offer looking across Phillip Island, San Remo, Kilcunda and beyond. As the track starts to descend, don't miss the stunning lookout point, just right of the track.

properties.name: Boronia Peak Track
properties.description:
Boronia Peak is one of the Grampians’ best hikes, offering epic views without the crowds of more popular trails. The path features a rocky climb to the summit, where you'll be rewarded with stunning vistas of Lake Fyans to the east and the Fyans Valley.

From Boronia Peak, you can continue on a trail that leads to the Brambuk Aboriginal Cultural Centre via the Fyans Creek (Barri Yalug) Loop. This extended walk is perfect for spotting local wildlife and enjoying spring wildflowers.

- Distance: 6.6km return
- Duration: 2 - 3 hours
- Grade: Medium
- Start/Finish: Tandara Road Car Park

properties.name: Burrong Falls and Walk
properties.description:
Short medium grade walk 640m return) Starts from the car park on Rose Creek Rd, approx. 9km from Mt Victory Rd. These Falls are best after rain. 

The walk takes you through a eucalypt forest where the track ends at a natural viewing platform overlooking the rock terrace of Burrong Falls.

Take a shower in the cold water while there!

properties.name: Beehive Falls and Track
properties.description:
Renowned as one of the most beautiful waterfalls in the Grampians, Beehive Falls is a popular tourist attraction within the Grampians region. Enjoy peace and tranquility at Beehive Falls.

Starting your walk at the beehive falls car park take the path leading to the base of the falls where seasonal rains fill fern-lined rock pools. The route is 2.8km return or 1 hour and 30 minutes with a medium level of fitness.

Visit the Beehive Falls after rain for the best views, and in spring for the surrounding wildflowers.

properties.name: Clematis Falls and Track
properties.description:
(2.4km return; 45min – 1hour) Clematis Falls is a simple walk and suitable for all. The easy track with a gentle grade starts at the back of the Halls Gap oval behind the club rooms on the fire trail. 

It’s mostly a flat track with some uneven rocky sections at the end.

Best viewed after rain, Clematis Falls is an easy stroll from Halls Gap. Wind your way through tall open forest to find yourself at the foot of the falls. Visit in spring and enjoy the many variety of wildflowers and keep your eyes peeled for native wildlife such as kangaroos and emus.

properties.name: Splitters Falls and Track
properties.description:
Splitters Falls is just a short walk from Halls Gap in the Grampians. From the center of town, follow the path along Stony Creek to Venus Baths, a series of rock pools popular for toe-dipping on warm days. From here, take the stairs to the tranquil setting of Splitters Falls.

Alternatively, you can drive up to the Wonderland car park and follow the river down stream past to see the Splitters Falls.

The best time to see the falls is Spring, as the wildflowers that surround the falls are popping with colour. The Splitters Falls is seasonal and may dry up over summer.

properties.name: Turret Falls
properties.description:
(2.2km return; 45min – 1hour) Turret Falls is named after its rock structure which looks like a turret. 

The falls are easy to find as you start the walk at the Wonderland carpark. From the carpark, you can follow the track along a steady incline that is not at all steep in any sections. 

As you walk along the track you will witness some incredible views of the river gorge.

properties.name: Great Ocean Road Day Tour
properties.description:
Visit the Great Ocean Road on this full day tour from Melbourne to witness one of the world's great drives. The dramatic, powerful and majestic Victorian coastline also known as the Ship Wreck Coast is one of Australia's most famous "must do" experiences. This full day tour on the Great Ocean Road extends from Geelong to Apollo Bay through Torquay and Lorne, featuring all the key natural and historical highlights that make this stretch of coast unique and all conducted aboard a comfortable coach with informative commentary given along the way.

Enjoy the Otway National Park, to the rugged beauty of the Twelve Apostle National Park and the Twelve Apostles to Loch Ard Gorge and Port Campbell shaped by the wild Southern Ocean this coastline will not fail to impress so be sure to bring your camera! Add in extras such as complimentary hotel pickups, free on-board Wi-Fi to browse as you travel and refreshments along the way to experience the best of the Great Ocean Road in comfort and style.

properties.name: Corner Store Cafe

Also serving shakes, smoothies, juices and other hot and cold beverages alongside toasted sandwiches and sweet and savoury snacks. 

The shop has a nostalgic vibe, complete with a mixed lolly bar and is an award-winning meeting place proving popular with locals and visitors. Come for the coffee and ice cream, stay for the tunes.

properties.name: Hawkesdale Golf Club and Recreatio Reserve
properties.description:
This is a Conservation Reserve.

From 18 April to 31 July 2024, a flock of 60 ewes will be grazing on the reserve. The camping area is unfenced, so if you prefer not to have sheep around your campsite, it may be best to visit after 31 July.

The Hawkesdale Racecourse Reserve, managed by a volunteer committee of local residents, spans 60 hectares and protects a significant area of volcanic plains grasslands, including some endangered flora and fauna.

Camping Information:

Campsites are located around the clubhouse and toilet block.
No camping or driving is allowed on the golf course.
Social golf has returned in 2023 after the Hawkesdale Golf Club's recess in 2003. A fee of $5 per person applies for use of the nine fairways. Golf clubs can be hired by prior arrangement; contact a volunteer using the provided mobile numbers.
Facilities:

- The campground offers toilets and is pet-friendly. However, dogs and cats must be restrained at all times. Pets that threaten native birds, animals, or grazing livestock will be banned.
- A donation is requested per night, and a three-day stay limit applies. Visitors are reminded to close the gate due to sheep grazing throughout the year.
- The reserve is accessible to RVs, camper trailers, caravans, and big rigs. 
- Tent camping is also allowed.
- There is no potable water on the reserve; all water is bore water and not suitable for human consumption.
- There are no rubbish bins, so please take your rubbish with you. Strictly No Fires at any time.
- No Cutting or Removal of Wood. 

Hawkesdale village has a Post Office with some general supplies available.

properties.name: Bright Splash Park and River Pool
properties.description:
Water from an old gold dredge bucket dumps down on the children waiting below, hitting the ground with a 'splash'. Gleeful shrieks fill the air. Nearby, a father and son are drenching each other with water cannons. Water squirts from the ground as children dart through rings of spray glistening in the sunlight.

Splayed out on the grass by the banks of the Ovens River are families picnicking, sunbaking, reading, and sleeping. Some swim in the river as the lifeguard watches on, edging as close to the dam wall as they can before the water cascades over. Water splashes as someone bombs from the springboard, and again as someone comes down the Rotary Slide. Under a small bridge, where Morses Creek meets the river, the smallest children wade in the shallows, filling buckets and cups and splashing about in their sunhats. It's little wonder the Bright Splash Park and River Pool has become a summertime favourite for families.

Set within Centenary Park and close to the cafes and eateries of the town centre, the Splash Park and River Pool has easy access to gas BBQs and picnic tables. A large children's playground, drinking water and public toilets are located in the adjoining Howitt Park.

Best of all, it's free!

The Splash Park and River Pool are officially open in the warmer months of the year when a lifeguard is on duty. The season generally runs up to the Easter long weekend before the splash park is switched off for winter when the river runs cold and fast.

The splash park uses a single-use water system that draws water from a bore and requires no chemical treatment. Used water is drained into the river, adding to the natural flows.

BIG4 Rutherglen Holiday Park is set on three acres, surrounded by sporting and recreational facilities. This pet friendly Rutherglen caravan park boasts self-contained cabins, powered caravan sites and unpowered camping sites with a centrally located amenities block, disabled facilities, coin operated laundry and a camp kitchen.

BIG4 Rutherglen Holiday Park is ideally situated next to the picturesque Lake King Wetlands, offering direct access to the local swimming pool, tennis courts, and Apex Park, which boasts a well-equipped playground, skate-park, and kids' cycle course. The Rutherglen Bowls Club and a welcoming golf course are also nearby. The surrounding area is famed for its vineyards, featuring outstanding restaurants and cafés. Just a short walk away, Main Street offers an eclectic mix of shops, pubs, and bakeries, as well as beautiful views around Lake King Wetlands.

After enjoying the region's wines, head back to the park for happy hour, where you can share your experiences with other guests while watching the sunset over the lake. In the winter months, gather around the cosy fire, and in the summer, find shade under the lovely gum trees lining the lake's edge.

properties.name: Nesting Ground Campground
properties.description:
Enjoy unpowered camping within the Winton Wetlands Reserve, where you can experience breathtaking sunrises and sunsets in a unique natural setting. Wake up to the sounds of birds as nature comes to life around you.

The campground offers a communal fire pit, picnic shelters, and Envirodome toilet facilities (no showers). Shower facilities are available at the nearby Mokoan Hub & Cafe.

Non-potable water is available, and gas stoves are recommended for cooking. The campground also provides direct access to the Greens Hill and Greens Spit walking tracks.

Please note that the campgrounds are closed on days declared Total Fire Bans.

properties.name: Dargo Hotel Campground
properties.description:
Victorian High Country -the iconic Dargo Hotel ?

Established back in 1898, there is FREE CAMPING adjacent to the Hotel and it’s literally creekside!

With a cold beer and warm feed beckoning we were set up in no time at all. Warm and welcoming. They have a standard pub menu... Well apart from the parmy section anyway which will leave you deliberating over which variety to order - there were about a dozen to choose from! Meals were reasonably priced and they were absolutely HUGE!

After we’d eaten we browsed the memorabilia on the walls and ceiling (!!) of the pub. There’s business cards, stubbie coolers, shirts and plenty of photos of local characters from over the years adorning just about every available space. It’s like a museum of life.

Dargo is nestled in the foothills of the legendary Dargo High Plains. We would’ve totally loved to spend a few days here as a base camp to explore some of the tracks within the region given it’s an entry point for the Alpine National Park, Avon Wilderness Park and Mitchell River National Park.

properties.name: Silverband Falls and Track
properties.description:
Silverband Falls is a gorgeous seasonal waterfall, accessed via an easy walk from the Silverband Falls Carpark. 

The waterfall was named by European Settlers in the 1800's, as the stunning stream of water resembles a silver band. Silverband Falls is an interesting spot as the water plunges down and disappears into the rocks at the base of the falls, travelling underground until the creek resurfaces about 50 metres away.

properties.name: Greg Ridsdale Memorial Caravan & Camping Park
properties.description: Small caravan park located at Bruthen- Buchan Road, Bruthen, Vic. Amenities include hot shower, toilet, camp kitchen and open fireplace.

properties.name: Lake Catani Campground
properties.description:
Camping is available from Melbourne Cup Weekend (beginning of November) to April inclusive. Advance bookings and payment are required.

Outside of the peak summer holiday period, bookings can be made up to 18 months ahead with new dates released every six months.

Bookings for the peak summer period (Christmas/New Year) open at 10am 1 September each year. Peak season periods fill quickly with bookings accepted on a first in, first served basis. Minimum stays apply.

There are  unpowered campsites available set among picturesque Snow Gum woodland. Each is marked by a numbered post. Camping is permitted only within the boundary of these sites.

Some of the sites are suitable for small caravans and campervans while others are for car camping and tents only. Walk-in campsites provide campers with even quieter surroundings. The maximum number of people per site is six.

The Horn Road and Lake Catani Road are closed on the Thursday after Kings Birthday long weekend. Both roads will reopen on 15 September dependent on snow and road conditions post winter.

properties.name: Fish Falls and Zumstiens Picnic Area
properties.description:
Fish Falls cascades 60 metres over terraced rocks into a pool below all year round.

Easily accessible from the popular Zumsteins Picnic Area the walk that leads up to the falls is a moderate 4.6 kilometre return trip that follows the MacKenzie River upstream.

Pack a picnic and rest your tired feet in the pool at the base of the falls, or climb the steps to the top. Adventurers, continue on the track to the famous MacKenzie Falls.

Fish Falls can be accessed as part of the MacKenzie River Walk from Zumsteins Car Park

properties.name: Andersons Mill Camping
properties.description: Free camping area with Long drop toilets and  Picnic tables

properties.name: Discovery Parks - Nagambie Lakes
properties.description:
Discovery Parks – Nagambie Lakes is nestled on the banks of the beautiful Goulburn River in Victoria’s historic gold-mining region. Perfect for water enthusiasts or anyone looking to unwind in nature, this park is an ideal spot for a relaxed family weekend or a longer stay to explore the area’s waterways, wineries, national parks, and wildlife reserves.

The charming town of Nagambie, with its old pubs, stunning gardens, and renowned wineries, is just a short distance away. However, once you enter our tree-lined park, you might never want to leave! With a range of family-friendly amenities like an infinity-edge pool, playground with a bouncing pillow, grass-court tennis, and a bicycle pump track, there’s always something fun to do.

Whether you’re visiting with family, flying solo, or in a group, our accommodations cater to all needs. The Deluxe Lakeside 3 Bedroom Cabins can sleep up to eight, while our Standard 2 Bedroom Cabins accommodate up to twelve. For a more private retreat, check out our Superior Riverside Spa Cabins.

Pets are welcome seasonally, so bring your furry friend along for the adventure!

properties.name: Little Creatures Brewery
properties.description:
What Little Creatures Brewery have constructed in Geelong is a bit like Willy Wonka’s Chocolate Factory … but for beer. A true brewery village experience, with a bustling Canteen and the colourful Mystery Lane.

Drop in, grab a Pale Ale and a bite to eat inside or outdoors and watch the brewers at work. Wander down Mystery Lane and see what you discover. On the first Sunday of every month in summer, Mystery Lane transforms into a craft market, supporting local makers to sell their wares. The menu is perfectly for sharing and working your way through the list of beers available on tap (or grab a pack or case to take-away as you leave). The canteen is even open for breakfast on weekends! 

Brewery tours are hosted daily, so jump aboard and learn more about how that delicious beer makes its way from brewery to bottle.

For the true beer enthusiast, White Rabbit Barrel Hall shares the same site and their range of beer is true to their philosophy of fermentation with imagination.

Narana seeks to build understanding of Aboriginal history and culture in a welcoming, friendly and relaxed atmosphere, through personal interaction with groups and individuals from all communities.

properties.name: Antarctic Journey at the Nobbies
properties.description:
Take a virtual journey to the world’s most extreme continent at Phillip Island's exciting Antarctic Journey at the Nobbies, a joint venture between WWF and Phillip Island Nature Parks.

Enjoy the ‘hands-on’ fun and interactive experiences in The Lab and feel the freeze in the Antarctic Chill Zone!

properties.name: Adventure Park Geelong
properties.description:
Dial up your summer at Victoria's biggest theme park, Adventure Park Geelong.

Offering awesome family fun and unlimited rides all day long, Adventure Park Geelong has some of the coolest rides in Australia, located just fifteen minutes from Geelong.

Make a gigantic splash on Victoria's coolest waterslides and rides, like the massive Tsunami and Tornado waterslides.

Take a spin on the new jeeps in the Little Buggy Speedway, where kids get to jump into the driver seat of their own miniature car and take a spin on the Crazy Coaster and Red Baron rides.

Speed down head first on the Six Lane Aqua Racer, or take the plunge on a two seater raft on The Gold Rush Rapids and Wild West Canyon waterslides, twisting and turning your way through the tunnels.

Adventure Park is all about the little kids, too. They'll love splashing about in the Tiny Tots Splashzone, a coral reef themed waterplay oasis with waterslides, waterfalls and spray cannons that will keep them cool and entertained for ages.

Bonito's Bay Water Play area is an endless interactive Caribbean Pirate Adventure playground towering three storeys and includes waterfalls, waterslides, water jets, a giant tipping bucket and more.

properties.name: Dinner Plain Mountain Resort
properties.description:
No matter what time of year you visit, the alpine village of Dinner Plain offers something special to enjoy. What's more, the renowned ski slopes and hiking trails of Hotham Alpine Resort are just 11km away. Here are some of the most popular things to do close to your doorstep at 1,500 meters altitude.

Top 5 things to Do in Summer:
- Ride the Dinner Plain Mountain Bike Park
- Hike The Razorback Trail to Mount Feathertop
- Cycle The Brabralung Trail (Dinner Plain to Hotham)
- Walk to Carmichael Falls
- Play a game of Frisbee Golf

Top 5 Things to Do in Winter:
- Go tobogganing on the Peashooter slope
- Take a sled dog ride around the village
- Cross-country ski The Brabralung (Dinner Plain to Hotham)
- Learn to ski on the Cobungra Platter Slope
- Snowshoe to JB Plain

During the ski season, there is an entry fee to visit Hotham Alpine Resort.

The Hotham Resort Entry Fee is not applicable if you plan to drive straight through to Dinner Plain along the Great Alpine Road without stopping. Beware, number plate cameras operate at Hotham and vehicles that stop within the resort area without a valid pass can be fined.

properties.name: Boort Lakes Holiday Park
properties.description:
It is on the shores of Little Lake Boort that the Boort Lakes Caravan Park is located. We are easy to find and offer the perfect venue for your holiday escape. Relax in our magnificent facilities and enjoy the spectacular views of the lake. You can see some of these great views in the slideshow below.

Boort Lakes Caravan Park offers cabin accommodation, powered and unpowered sites. Simply use our contact page to either email, phone or fax us to discuss your holiday experience.

properties.name: Mount Hotham Alpine Village
properties.description:
Here at Hotham, Australia’s highest alpine village, you can swap city life for crisp mountain air and some of Australia's best vistas; from breathtaking misty sunrises to unforgettable 360-degree views of the surrounding rugged mountain ranges. 

Hotham is a year round resort, so winter-time means all your favourite snow-based activities are available and the summer sun brings out stunning landscapes and plenty of trails for hiking, biking and trail running - so there's always a new adventure to be had.

properties.name: Boundary Bend General Store and Caravan Park
properties.description:
The Boundary Bend General Store & Caravan Park, also known as Murray River Caravan Park & General Store, is a simple yet convenient spot for travelers along the Murray Valley Highway in Victoria. This small campground offers both powered and unpowered sites with ample shade. Guests appreciate the cleanliness of the area, though the facilities are somewhat dated. The park provides essential amenities, including a general store, fuel station, and café, making it a handy stop for essentials.

The caravan park is pet-friendly and accommodates motorhomes and caravans. However, some reviews note that there are no fires allowed, and amenities are basic, with no additional recreational facilities onsite. It’s an affordable option, especially for those who don't require luxury, and its proximity to the river offers scenic views and a peaceful atmosphere

Nathalia Motel and Holiday Park is only a five minute walk to the centre of town.

They provide 13 comfortable motel rooms, one spa room and cabins all with air conditioning, and LCD televisions. Caravans and powered sites are also available.

Facilities include an adult and a children's pool, with shade sails a...
